# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rocket-propulsion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] An **ion thruster**, **ion drive**, or **ion engine** is a form of electric propulsion used for spacecraft propulsion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] An ion thruster creates a cloud of positive ions from a neutral gas by ionizing it to extract some electrons from its atoms.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The ions are then accelerated using electricity to create thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters are categorized as either electrostatic or electromagnetic.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Electrostatic thruster ions are accelerated by the Coulomb force along the electric field direction.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Temporarily stored electrons are reinjected by a *neutralizer* in the cloud of ions after it has passed through the electrostatic grid, so the gas becomes neutral again and can freely disperse in space without any further electrical interaction with the thruster.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters in operation typically consume 1–7 kW of power, have exhaust velocities around 20–50 km/s (12–30 mi/s, *I*sp 2000–5000 s), and possess thrusts of 25–250 mN and a propulsive efficiency of 65–80%; experimental ion thrusters have achieved 100 kW (130 hp), 5 N (1.1 lbf).
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The 1998 *Deep Space 1* spacecraft changed velocity by 4.3 km/s (2.7 mi/s) with its ion thruster, and consumed 73.4 kg (162 lb) of xenon.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The 2007 *Dawn* spacecraft achieved velocity change of 11.5 km/s (7.1 mi/s), though with less efficiency, having consumed 425 kg (937 lb) of xenon.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrust engines are generally practical only in the vacuum of space as the engine's minuscule thrust cannot overcome any significant air resistance without radical design changes, as may be found in the 'Atmosphere Breathing Electric Propulsion' concept.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) has created designs that are able to fly for short distances and at low speeds at ground level, using ultra-light materials and low drag aerofoils.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] An ion engine cannot usually generate sufficient thrust to achieve initial liftoff from any celestial body with significant surface gravity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] For these reasons, spacecraft must rely on other methods such as conventional chemical rockets or non-rocket launch technologies to reach their initial orbit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Konstantin Tsiolkovsky first suggested the concept of ion thruster in 1911.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The technique was recommended for near-vacuum conditions at high altitude, but thrust was demonstrated with ionized air streams at atmospheric pressure.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The idea appeared again in Hermann Oberth's *Wege zur Raumschiffahrt* (1929; *Ways to Spaceflight*), where he explained his thoughts on the mass savings of electric propulsion, predicted its use in spacecraft propulsion and attitude control, and advocated electrostatic acceleration of charged gases.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The concept of an ion thruster spacecraft was first popularized in a science fiction story by American Jack Williamson in 1947.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It subsequently became a staple of genre science fiction stories.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A working ion thruster was built by Harold R.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Kaufman in 1959 at the NASA Glenn Research Center facilities.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It was similar to a gridded electrostatic ion thruster and used mercury for propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Suborbital tests were conducted during the 1960s and in 1964, and the engine was sent into a suborbital flight aboard the Space Electric Rocket Test-1 (SERT-1).
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It successfully operated for the planned 31 minutes before falling to Earth.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This test was followed by an orbital test, SERT-2, in 1970.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] On the 12 October 1964 Voskhod 1 carried out tests with ion thrusters that had been attached to the exterior of the spacecraft.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] An alternate form of electric propulsion, the Hall-effect thruster, was studied independently in the United States and the Soviet Union in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Hall-effect thrusters operated on Soviet satellites from 1972 until the late 1990s, mainly used for satellite stabilization in north–south and in east–west directions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Some 100–200 engines completed missions on Soviet and Russian satellites.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Soviet thruster design was introduced to the West in 1992 after a team of electric propulsion specialists, under the support of the Ballistic Missile Defense Organization, visited Soviet laboratories.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters use beams of ions (electrically charged atoms or molecules) to create thrust in accordance with momentum conservation.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The method of accelerating the ions varies, but all designs take advantage of the charge/mass ratio of the ions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This ratio means that relatively small potential differences can create high exhaust velocities.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This reduces the amount of reaction mass or propellant required, but increases the amount of specific power required compared to chemical rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters are therefore able to achieve high specific impulses.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The drawback of the low thrust is low acceleration because the mass of the electric power unit directly correlates with the amount of power.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This low thrust makes ion thrusters unsuited for launching spacecraft into orbit, but effective for in-space propulsion over longer periods of time.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Electric power for ion thrusters is usually provided by solar panels.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] However, for sufficiently large distances from the sun, nuclear power may be used.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] In each case, the power supply mass is proportional to the peak power that can be supplied, and both provide, for this application, almost no limit to the energy.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Electric thrusters tend to produce low thrust, which results in low acceleration.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Defining $1g=9.81\;\mathrm {m/s^{2}}$ , the standard gravitational acceleration of Earth, and noting that $F=ma\implies a=F/m$ , this can be analyzed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] An NSTAR thruster producing a thrust force of 92 mN will accelerate a satellite with a mass of 1 ton by 0.092 N / 1000 kg = 9.2×10−5 m/s2 (or 9.38×10−6 *g*).
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] However, this acceleration can be sustained for months or years at a time, in contrast to the very short burns of chemical rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The ion thruster is not the most promising type of electrically powered spacecraft propulsion, but it is the most successful in practice to date.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] An ion drive would require two days to accelerate a car to highway speed in vacuum.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The technical characteristics, especially thrust, are considerably inferior to the prototypes described in literature.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Technical capabilities are limited by the space charge created by ions, which limits the thrust density‍— the force per cross-sectional area of the engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The power imparted to the exhaust increases with the square of exhaust velocity while thrust increase is linear.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Conversely, chemical rockets provide high thrust, but are limited in total impulse by the small amount of energy that can be stored chemically in the propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Given the practical weight of suitable power sources, the acceleration from an ion thruster is frequently less than one-thousandth of standard gravity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] However, since they operate as electric (or electrostatic) motors, they convert a greater fraction of input power into kinetic exhaust power.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Chemical rockets operate as heat engines, and Carnot's theorem limits the exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Gridded electrostatic ion thrusters development started in the 1960s and, since then, they have been used for commercial satellite propulsion and scientific missions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Their main feature is that the propellant ionization process is physically separated from the ion acceleration process.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The ionization process takes place in the discharge chamber, where by bombarding the propellant with energetic electrons, as the energy transferred ejects valence electrons from the propellant gas's atoms.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] These electrons can be provided by a hot cathode filament and accelerated through the potential difference towards an anode.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Alternatively, the electrons can be accelerated by an oscillating induced electric field created by an alternating electromagnet, which results in a self-sustaining discharge without a cathode (radio frequency ion thruster).
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The positively charged ions are extracted by a system consisting of 2 or 3 multi-aperture grids.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] After entering the grid system near the plasma sheath, the ions are accelerated by the potential difference between the first grid and second grid (called the screen grid and the accelerator grid, respectively) to the final ion energy of (typically) 1–2 keV, which generates thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters emit a beam of positively charged ions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] To keep the spacecraft from accumulating a charge, another cathode is placed near the engine to emit electrons into the ion beam, leaving the propellant electrically neutral.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This prevents the beam of ions from being attracted (and returning) to the spacecraft, which would cancel the thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Hall-effect thrusters accelerate ions by means of an electric potential between a cylindrical anode and a negatively charged plasma that forms the cathode.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The bulk of the propellant (typically xenon) is introduced near the anode, where it ionizes and flows toward the cathode; ions accelerate towards and through it, picking up electrons as they leave to neutralize the beam and leave the thruster at high velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The anode is at one end of a cylindrical tube.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] In the center is a spike that is wound to produce a radial magnetic field between it and the surrounding tube.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The ions are largely unaffected by the magnetic field, since they are too massive.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] However, the electrons produced near the end of the spike to create the cathode are trapped by the magnetic field and held in place by their attraction to the anode.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Some of the electrons spiral down towards the anode, circulating around the spike in a Hall current.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] When they reach the anode they impact the uncharged propellant and cause it to be ionized, before finally reaching the anode and completing the circuit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Field-emission electric propulsion (FEEP) thrusters may use caesium or indium propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The design comprises a small propellant reservoir that stores the liquid metal, a narrow tube or a system of parallel plates that the liquid flows through and an accelerator (a ring or an elongated aperture in a metallic plate) about a millimeter past the tube end.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Caesium and indium are used due to their high atomic weights, low ionization potentials and low melting points.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Once the liquid metal reaches the end of the tube, an electric field applied between the emitter and the accelerator causes the liquid surface to deform into a series of protruding cusps, or *Taylor cones*.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] At a sufficiently high applied voltage, positive ions are extracted from the tips of the cones.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The electric field created by the emitter and the accelerator then accelerates the ions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] An external source of electrons neutralizes the positively charged ion stream to prevent charging of the spacecraft.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Pulsed inductive thrusters (PITs) use pulses instead of continuous thrust and have the ability to run on power levels on the order of megawatts (MW).
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] PITs consist of a large coil encircling a cone shaped tube that emits the propellant gas.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] For each pulse, a large charge builds up in a group of capacitors behind the coil and is then released.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This creates a current that moves circularly in the direction of jθ.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The current then creates a magnetic field in the outward radial direction (Br), which then creates a current in the gas that has just been released in the opposite direction of the original current.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This opposite current ionizes the ammonia.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The positively charged ions are accelerated away from the engine due to the electric field jθ crossing the magnetic field Br, due to the Lorentz force.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Magnetoplasmadynamic (MPD) thrusters and lithium Lorentz force accelerator (LiLFA) thrusters use roughly the same idea.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The LiLFA thruster builds on the MPD thruster.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Hydrogen, argon, ammonia and nitrogen can be used as propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] In a certain configuration, the ambient gas in low Earth orbit (LEO) can be used as a propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The gas enters the main chamber where it is ionized into plasma by the electric field between the anode and the cathode.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This plasma then conducts electricity between the anode and the cathode, closing the circuit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This new current creates a magnetic field around the cathode, which crosses with the electric field, thereby accelerating the plasma due to the Lorentz force.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The LiLFA thruster uses the same general idea as the MPD thruster, though with two main differences.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] First, the LiLFA uses lithium vapor, which can be stored as a solid.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The other difference is that the single cathode is replaced by multiple, smaller cathode rods packed into a hollow cathode tube.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] MPD cathodes are easily corroded due to constant contact with the plasma.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] In the LiLFA thruster, the lithium vapor is injected into the hollow cathode and is not ionized to its plasma form/corrode the cathode rods until it exits the tube.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The plasma is then accelerated using the same Lorentz force.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] In 2013, the Russian company Chemical Automatics Design Bureau successfully conducted a bench test of their MPD engine for long-distance space travel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Electrodeless plasma thrusters have two unique features: the removal of the anode and cathode electrodes and the ability to throttle the engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The removal of the electrodes eliminates erosion, which limits lifetime on other ion engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Neutral gas is first ionized by electromagnetic waves and then transferred to another chamber where it is accelerated by an oscillating electric and magnetic field, also known as the ponderomotive force.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This separation of the ionization and acceleration stages allows throttling of propellant flow, which then changes the thrust magnitude and specific impulse values.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A helicon double layer thruster is a type of plasma thruster that ejects high velocity ionized gas to provide thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] In this design, gas is injected into a tubular chamber (the *source tube*) with one open end.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Radio frequency AC power (at 13.56 MHz in the prototype design) is coupled into a specially shaped antenna wrapped around the chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The electromagnetic wave emitted by the antenna causes the gas to break down and form a plasma.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The antenna then excites a helicon wave in the plasma, which further heats it.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The device has a roughly constant magnetic field in the source tube (supplied by solenoids in the prototype), but the magnetic field diverges and rapidly decreases in magnitude away from the source region and might be thought of as a kind of magnetic nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] In operation, a sharp boundary separates the high density plasma inside the source region and the low density plasma in the exhaust, which is associated with a sharp change in electrical potential.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Plasma properties change rapidly across this boundary, which is known as a *current-free electric double layer*.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The electrical potential is much higher inside the source region than in the exhaust and this serves both to confine most of the electrons and to accelerate the ions away from the source region.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Enough electrons escape the source region to ensure that the plasma in the exhaust is neutral overall.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The proposed Variable Specific Impulse Magnetoplasma Rocket (VASIMR) functions by using radio waves to ionize a propellant into a plasma, and then using a magnetic field to accelerate the plasma out of the back of the rocket engine to generate thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The VASIMR is currently being developed by Ad Astra Rocket Company, headquartered in Houston, Texas, with help from Canada-based Nautel, producing the 200 kW RF generators for ionizing propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Some of the components and "plasma shoots" experiments are tested in a laboratory settled in Liberia, Costa Rica.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This project is led by former NASA astronaut Franklin Chang-Díaz (CRC-USA).
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A 200 kW VASIMR test engine was in discussion to be fitted in the exterior of the International Space Station, as part of the plan to test the VASIMR in space; however, plans for this test onboard ISS were canceled in 2015 by NASA, with a free flying VASIMR test being discussed by Ad Astra instead.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] An envisioned 200 MW engine could reduce the duration of flight from Earth to Jupiter or Saturn from six years to fourteen months, and Mars from 7 months to 39 days.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Under a research grant from the NASA Lewis Research Center during the 1980s and 1990s, Martin C.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Hawley and Jes Asmussen led a team of engineers in developing a microwave electrothermal thruster (MET).
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] In the discharge chamber, microwave (MW) energy flows into the center containing a high level of ions (I), causing neutral species in the gaseous propellant to ionize.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Excited species flow out (FES) through the low ion region (II) to a neutral region (III) where the ions complete their recombination, replaced with the flow of neutral species (FNS) towards the center.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Meanwhile, energy is lost to the chamber walls through heat conduction and convection (HCC), along with radiation (Rad).
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The remaining energy absorbed into the gaseous propellant is converted into thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A theoretical propulsion system has been proposed, based on alpha particles (He2+ or 4 2He2+ indicating a helium ion with a +2 charge) emitted from a radioisotope uni-directionally through a hole in its chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A neutralising electron gun would produce a tiny amount of thrust with high specific impulse in the order of millions of seconds due to the high relativistic speed of alpha particles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A variant of this uses a graphite-based grid with a static DC high voltage to increase thrust as graphite has high transparency to alpha particles if it is also irradiated with short wave UV light at the correct wavelength from a solid-state emitter.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It also permits lower energy and longer half-life sources which would be advantageous for a space application.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Helium backfill has also been suggested as a way to increase electron mean free path.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters' low thrust requires continuous operation for a long time to achieve the necessary change in velocity (delta-v) for a particular mission.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters are designed to provide continuous operation for intervals of weeks to years.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The lifetime of electrostatic ion thrusters is limited by several processes.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] In electrostatic gridded designs, charge-exchange ions produced by the beam ions with the neutral gas flow can be accelerated towards the negatively biased accelerator grid and cause grid erosion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] End-of-life is reached when either the grid structure fails or the holes in the grid become large enough that ion extraction is substantially affected – e.g., by the occurrence of electron backstreaming.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Grid erosion cannot be avoided and is the major lifetime-limiting factor.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Thorough grid design and material selection enable lifetimes of 20,000 hours or more.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A test of the NASA Solar Technology Application Readiness (NSTAR) electrostatic ion thruster resulted in 30,472 hours (roughly 3.5 years) of continuous thrust at maximum power.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Post-test examination indicated the engine was not approaching failure.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The NASA Evolutionary Xenon Thruster (NEXT) project operated continuously for more than 48,000 hours.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The test was conducted in a high-vacuum test chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Over the course of the test, which lasted more than five and a half years, the engine consumed approximately 870 kilograms of xenon propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The total impulse generated would require over 10,000 kilograms of conventional rocket propellant for a similar application.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Hall-effect thrusters suffer from strong erosion of the ceramic discharge chamber by impact of energetic ions: a test reported in 2010 showed erosion of around 1 mm per hundred hours of operation, though this is inconsistent with observed on-orbit lifetimes of a few thousand hours.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The Advanced Electric Propulsion System (AEPS) is expected to accumulate about 5,000 hours and the design aims to achieve a flight model that offers a half-life of at least 23,000 hours and a full life of about 50,000 hours.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ionization energy represents a large percentage of the energy needed to run ion drives.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The ideal propellant is thus easy to ionize and has a high mass/ionization energy ratio.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] In addition, the propellant should not erode the thruster to any great degree, so as to permit long life, and should not contaminate the vehicle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Many designs use xenon gas, as it is easy to ionize, has a reasonably high atomic number, is inert and causes low erosion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] However, xenon is globally in short supply and expensive (approximately $3,000 per kg in 2021).
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Some older ion thruster designs used mercury propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] However, mercury is toxic, tended to contaminate spacecraft, and was difficult to feed accurately.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A modern commercial prototype may be using mercury successfully however, mercury was formally banned as a propellant in 2022 by the Minamata Convention on Mercury.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] From 2018–2023, krypton was used to fuel the Hall-effect thrusters aboard Starlink internet satellites, in part due to its lower cost than conventional xenon propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Starlink V2-mini satellites have since switched to argon Hall-effect thrusters, providing higher specific impulse.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Other propellants, such as bismuth and iodine, show promise both for gridless designs such as Hall-effect thrusters, and gridded ion thrusters.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Iodine was used as a propellant for the first time in space, in the NPT30-I2 gridded ion thruster by ThrustMe, on board the Beihangkongshi-1 mission launched in November 2020, with an extensive report published a year later in the journal *Nature*.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The CubeSat Ambipolar Thruster (CAT) used on the Mars Array of Ionospheric Research Satellites Using the CubeSat Ambipolar Thruster (MARS-CAT) mission also proposes to use solid iodine as the propellant to minimize storage volume.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] VASIMR design (and other plasma-based engines) are theoretically able to use practically any material for propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] However, tests show the most practical propellant is argon, which is relatively abundant and inexpensive.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thruster efficiency is the kinetic energy of the exhaust jet emitted per second divided by the electrical power into the device.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Overall system energy efficiency is determined by the propulsive efficiency, which depends on vehicle speed and exhaust speed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Some thrusters can vary exhaust speed in operation, but all can be designed with different exhaust speeds.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] At the lower end of specific impulse, *I*sp, the overall efficiency drops because ionization takes up a larger percentage energy and at the high end propulsive efficiency is reduced.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Optimal efficiencies and exhaust velocities for any given mission can be calculated to give minimum overall cost.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters have many in-space propulsion applications.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The best applications make use of the long mission interval when significant thrust is not needed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Examples of this include orbit transfers, attitude adjustments, drag compensation for low Earth orbits, fine adjustments for scientific missions and cargo transport between propellant depots, e.g., for chemical fuels.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters can also be used for interplanetary and deep-space missions where acceleration rates are not crucial.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters are seen as the best solution for these missions, as they require high change in velocity but do not require rapid acceleration.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Continuous thrust over long durations can reach high velocities while consuming far less propellant than traditional chemical rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion propulsion systems were first demonstrated in space by the NASA Lewis (now Glenn Research Center) missions Space Electric Rocket Test (SERT)-1 and SERT-2A.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A SERT-1 suborbital flight was launched on 20 July 1964, and successfully proved that the technology operated as predicted in space.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] These were electrostatic ion thrusters using mercury and caesium as the reaction mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] SERT-2A, launched on 4 February 1970, verified the operation of two mercury ion engines for thousands of running hours.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ion thrusters are routinely used for station-keeping on commercial and military communication satellites in geosynchronous orbit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The Soviet Union pioneered this field, using stationary plasma thrusters (SPTs) on satellites starting in the early 1970s.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Two geostationary satellites (ESA's Artemis in 2001–2003 and the United States military's AEHF-1 in 2010–2012) used the ion thruster to change orbit after the chemical-propellant engine failed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Boeing began using ion thrusters for station-keeping in 1997 and planned in 2013–2014 to offer a variant on their 702 platform, with no chemical engine and ion thrusters for orbit raising; this permits a significantly lower launch mass for a given satellite capability.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] AEHF-2 used a chemical engine to raise perigee to 16,330 km (10,150 mi) and proceeded to geosynchronous orbit using electric propulsion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] China's Tiangong space station is fitted with ion thrusters.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Its Tianhe core module is propelled by both chemical thrusters and four Hall-effect thrusters, which are used to adjust and maintain the station's orbit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The development of the Hall-effect thrusters is considered a sensitive topic in China, with scientists "working to improve the technology without attracting attention".
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Hall-effect thrusters are created with crewed mission safety in mind with effort to prevent erosion and damage caused by the accelerated ion particles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A magnetic field and specially designed ceramic shield was created to repel damaging particles and maintain integrity of the thrusters.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] According to the Chinese Academy of Sciences, the ion drive used on Tiangong has burned continuously for 8,240 hours without a glitch, indicating their suitability for the Chinese space station's designated 15-year lifespan.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This is the world's first Hall thruster on a human-rated mission.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] SpaceX's Starlink satellite constellation uses Hall-effect thrusters powered by krypton or argon to raise orbit, perform maneuvers, and de-orbit at the end of their use.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] ESA's Gravity Field and Steady-State Ocean Circulation Explorer (GOCE) was launched on 16 March 2009.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It used ion propulsion throughout its twenty-month mission to combat the air-drag it experienced in its low orbit (altitude of 255 kilometres) before intentionally deorbiting on 11 November 2013.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] NASA developed the NSTAR ion engine for use in interplanetary science missions beginning in the late 1990s.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It was space-tested in the space probe *Deep Space 1*, launched in 1998.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This was the first use of electric propulsion as the interplanetary propulsion system on a science mission.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Based on the NASA design criteria, Hughes Research Labs developed the Xenon Ion Propulsion System (XIPS) for performing station keeping on geosynchronous satellites.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Hughes (EDD) manufactured the NSTAR thruster used on the spacecraft.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The Japanese Aerospace Exploration Agency's *Hayabusa* space probe was launched in 2003 and rendezvoused with the asteroid 25143 Itokawa.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It was powered by four xenon ion engines, which used microwave electron cyclotron resonance to ionize the propellant and an erosion-resistant carbon/carbon-composite material for its acceleration grid.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Although the ion engines on *Hayabusa* experienced technical difficulties, in-flight reconfiguration allowed one of the four engines to be repaired and allowed the mission to successfully return to Earth.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Hayabusa2, launched in 2014, was based on Hayabusa.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The European Space Agency's satellite *SMART-1* launched in 2003 using a Snecma PPS-1350-G Hall thruster to get from GTO to lunar orbit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] This satellite completed its mission on 3 September 2006, in a controlled collision on the Moon's surface, after a trajectory deviation so scientists could see the 3-meter crater the impact created on the visible side of the Moon.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] LISA Pathfinder is an ESA spacecraft launched in 2015 to orbit the Sun-Earth L1 point.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It does not use ion thrusters as its primary propulsion system, but uses both colloid thrusters and FEEP for precise attitude control – the low thrusts of these propulsion devices make it possible to move the spacecraft incremental distances accurately.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] ESA's BepiColombo mission was launched to Mercury on 20 October 2018.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It uses ion thrusters in combination with swing-bys to get to Mercury, where a chemical rocket will complete orbit insertion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] NASA's Double Asteroid Redirection Test (DART) was launched in 2021 and operated its NEXT-C xenon ion thruster for about 1,000 hours to reach the target asteroid on 28 September 2022.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] NASA's Psyche spacecraft was launched in 2023 and is operating its SPT-140 xenon ion thruster in order to reach asteroid 16 Psyche in August 2029.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] CNSA's *Tianwen-2* was launched in May 2025, to explore the co-orbital near-Earth asteroid 469219 Kamoʻoalewa and the active asteroid 311P/PanSTARRS and collecting samples of the regolith of Kamo'oalewa.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The MARS-CAT (Mars Array of ionospheric Research Satellites using the CubeSat Ambipolar Thruster) mission is a two 6U CubeSat concept mission to study Mars' ionosphere.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The mission would investigate its plasma and magnetic structure, including transient plasma structures, magnetic field structure, magnetic activity and correlation with solar wind drivers.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The CAT thruster is now called the RF thruster and manufactured by Phase Four.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Landis proposed using an ion thruster powered by a space-based laser, in conjunction with a lightsail, to propel an interstellar probe.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] As of March 2011, a future launch of an Ad Astra VF-200 200 kW VASIMR electromagnetic thruster was under consideration for testing on the International Space Station (ISS).
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] However, in 2015, NASA ended plans for flying the VF-200 to the ISS.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] A NASA spokesperson stated that the ISS "was not an ideal demonstration platform for the desired performance level of the engines".
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Ad Astra stated that tests of a VASIMR thruster on the ISS would remain an option after a future in-space demonstration.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The VF-200 would have been a flight version of the VX-200.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Since the available power from the ISS is less than 200 kW, the ISS VASIMR would have included a trickle-charged battery system allowing for 15 minutes pulses of thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] Hydrogen is generated by the ISS as a by-product and is vented into space.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] NASA previously worked on a 50 kW Hall-effect thruster for the ISS, but work was stopped in 2005.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] The Power and Propulsion Element (PPE) is a module on the Lunar Gateway that provides power generation and propulsion capabilities.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It was planned to be launched on a Falcon Heavy no earlier than 2027.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] It would probably have used the 50 kW Advanced Electric Propulsion System (AEPS) under development at NASA Glenn Research Center and Aerojet Rocketdyne.
[src:rocket-propulsion/ion-thruster] However, NASA decided to cancel Gateway in 2026 and instead shifted its focus on the construction of a lunar surface base, leaving the future of the thruster uncertain.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] A **liquid-propellant rocket** or **liquid rocket** uses a rocket engine burning liquid propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] (Alternate approaches use gaseous or solid propellants.) Liquids are desirable propellants because they have reasonably high density and their combustion products have high specific impulse (*I*sp).
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] This allows the volume of the propellant tanks to be relatively low.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Liquid rockets can be monopropellant rockets using a single type of propellant, or bipropellant rockets using two types of propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Tripropellant rockets using three types of propellant are rare.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Liquid oxidizer propellants are also used in hybrid rockets, with some of the advantages of a solid rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] **Bipropellant liquid rockets** use a liquid fuel such as liquid hydrogen or RP-1, and a liquid oxidizer such as liquid oxygen.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The engine may be a cryogenic rocket engine, where the fuel and oxidizer, such as hydrogen and oxygen, are gases which have been liquefied at very low temperatures.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Most designs of liquid rocket engines are throttleable for variable thrust operation.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Some allow control of the propellant mixture ratio (ratio at which oxidizer and fuel are mixed).
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Some can be shut down and, with a suitable ignition system or self-igniting propellant, restarted.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Hybrid rockets apply a liquid or gaseous oxidizer to a solid fuel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Liquid rocket engines have tankage and pipes to store and transfer propellant, an injector system and one or more combustion chambers with associated nozzles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Typical liquid propellants have densities roughly similar to water, approximately 0.7 to 1.4 g/cm3 (0.025 to 0.051 lb/cu in).
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] An exception is liquid hydrogen which has a much lower density, while requiring only relatively modest pressure to prevent vaporization.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The density and low pressure of liquid propellants permit lightweight tankage: approximately 1% of the contents for dense propellants and around 10% for liquid hydrogen.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The increased tank mass is due to liquid hydrogen's low density and the mass of the required insulation.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] For injection into the combustion chamber, the propellant pressure at the injectors needs to be greater than the chamber pressure.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Suitable pumps usually use centrifugal turbopumps due to their high power and light weight, although reciprocating pumps have been employed in the past.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Turbopumps are usually lightweight and can give excellent performance; with an on-Earth weight well under 1% of the thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Indeed, overall thrust to weight ratios including a turbopump have been as high as 155:1 with the SpaceX Merlin 1D rocket engine and up to 180:1 with the vacuum version.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Instead of a pump, some designs use a tank of a high-pressure inert gas such as helium to pressurize the propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] These rockets often provide lower delta-v because the mass of the pressurant tankage reduces performance.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In some designs for high altitude or vacuum use the tankage mass can be acceptable.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The major components of a rocket engine are therefore the combustion chamber (thrust chamber), pyrotechnic igniter, propellant feed system, valves, regulators, propellant tanks and the rocket engine nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] For feeding propellants to the combustion chamber, liquid-propellant engines are either pressure-fed or pump-fed, with pump-fed engines working in a variety of engine cycles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Liquid propellants are often pumped into the combustion chamber with a lightweight centrifugal turbopump.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Recently, some aerospace companies have used electric pumps with batteries.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In simpler, small engines, an inert gas stored in a tank at a high pressure is sometimes used instead of pumps to force propellants into the combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] These engines may have a higher mass ratio, but are usually more reliable, and are therefore used widely in satellites for orbit maintenance.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Thousands of combinations of fuels and oxidizers have been tried over the years.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Lightweight foam insulation on the Space Shuttle external tank led to the Space Shuttle *Columbia*'s destruction, as a piece broke loose, damaged its wing and caused it to break up on atmospheric reentry.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Liquid methane/LNG has several advantages over LH2.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Its performance (max. specific impulse) is lower than that of LH2 but higher than that of RP1 (kerosene) and solid propellants, and its higher density, similarly to other hydrocarbon fuels, provides higher thrust to volume ratios than LH2, although its density is not as high as that of RP1.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] This makes it specially attractive for reusable launch systems because higher density allows for smaller motors, propellant tanks and associated systems.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] LNG also burns with less or no soot (less or no coking) than RP1, which eases reusability when compared with it, and LNG and RP1 burn cooler than LH2 so LNG and RP1 do not deform the interior structures of the engine as much.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] This means that engines that burn LNG can be reused more than those that burn RP1 or LH2.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Unlike engines that burn LH2, both RP1 and LNG engines can be designed with a shared shaft with a single turbine and two turbopumps, one each for LOX and LNG/RP1.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In space, LNG does not need heaters to keep it liquid, unlike RP1.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] LNG is less expensive, being readily available in large quantities.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] It can be stored for more prolonged periods of time, and is less explosive than LH2.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Many non-cryogenic bipropellants are hypergolic (self igniting).
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Because of this, mixtures of hydrazine or its derivatives in combination with nitrogen oxides are generally used for such applications, but are toxic and carcinogenic.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Consequently, to improve handling, some crew vehicles such as Dream Chaser and Space Ship Two plan to use hybrid rockets with non-toxic fuel and oxidizer combinations.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The injector implementation in liquid rockets determines the percentage of the theoretical performance of the nozzle that can be achieved.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] A poor injector performance causes unburnt propellant to leave the engine, giving poor efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Additionally, injectors are also usually key in reducing thermal loads on the nozzle; by increasing the proportion of fuel around the edge of the chamber, this gives much lower temperatures on the walls of the nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Injectors can be as simple as a number of small diameter holes arranged in carefully constructed patterns through which the fuel and oxidizer travel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The speed of the flow is determined by the square root of the pressure drop across the injectors, the shape of the hole and other details such as the density of the propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The first injectors used on the V-2 created parallel jets of fuel and oxidizer which then combusted in the chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Injectors today classically consist of a number of small holes which aim jets of fuel and oxidizer so that they collide at a point in space a short distance away from the injector plate.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] This helps to break the flow up into small droplets that burn more easily.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The pintle injector permits good mixture control of fuel and oxidizer over a wide range of flow rates.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The pintle injector was used in the Apollo Lunar Module engines (Descent Propulsion System) and the Kestrel engine, it is currently used in the Merlin engine on Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Valentin Glushko invented the centripetal injector in the early 1930s, and it has been almost universally used in Russian engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Rotational motion is applied to the liquid (and sometimes the two propellants are mixed), then it is expelled through a small hole, where it forms a cone-shaped sheet that rapidly atomizes.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Goddard's first liquid engine used a single impinging injector.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] German scientists in WWII experimented with impinging injectors on flat plates, used successfully in the Wasserfall missile.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] To avoid instabilities such as *chugging,* which is a relatively low speed oscillation, the engine must be designed with enough pressure drop across the injectors to render the flow largely independent of the chamber pressure.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] This pressure drop is normally achieved by using at least 20% of the chamber pressure across the injectors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Nevertheless, particularly in larger engines, a high speed combustion oscillation is easily triggered, and these are not well understood.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] These high speed oscillations tend to disrupt the gas side boundary layer of the engine, and this can cause the cooling system to rapidly fail, destroying the engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] These kinds of oscillations are much more common on large engines, and plagued the development of the Saturn V, but were finally overcome.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Some combustion chambers, such as those of the RS-25 engine, use Helmholtz resonators as damping mechanisms to stop particular resonant frequencies from growing.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] To prevent these issues the RS-25 injector design instead went to a lot of effort to vaporize the propellant prior to injection into the combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Although many other features were used to ensure that instabilities could not occur, later research showed that these other features were unnecessary, and the gas phase combustion worked reliably.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Testing for stability often involves the use of small explosives.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] These are detonated within the chamber during operation, and causes an impulsive excitation.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] By examining the pressure trace of the chamber to determine how quickly the effects of the disturbance die away, it is possible to estimate the stability and redesign features of the chamber if required.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] For liquid-propellant rockets, four different ways of powering the injection of the propellant into the chamber are in common use.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Fuel and oxidizer must be pumped into the combustion chamber against the pressure of the hot gasses being burned, and engine power is limited by the rate at which propellant can be pumped into the combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] For atmospheric or launcher use, high pressure, and thus high power, engine cycles are desirable to minimize gravity drag.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] For orbital use, lower power cycles are usually fine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The propellants are forced in from pressurised (relatively heavy) tanks.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The heavy tanks mean that a relatively low pressure is optimal, limiting engine power, but all the fuel is burned, allowing high efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The pressurant used is frequently helium due to its lack of reactivity and low density.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The electric motor is powered by a battery pack.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] design, but at the expense of the extra dry mass of the battery pack.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] A small percentage of the propellants are burnt in a preburner to power a turbopump and then exhausted through a separate nozzle, or low down on the main one.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] This results in a reduction in efficiency since the exhaust contributes little or no thrust, but the pump turbines can be very large, allowing for high power engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] turbines to pump propellant, then is exhausted.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Since not all propellant flows through the main combustion chamber, the tap-off cycle is considered an open-cycle engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Cryogenic fuel (hydrogen, or methane) is used to cool the walls of the combustion chamber and nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Absorbed heat vaporizes and expands the fuel which is then used to drive the turbopumps before it enters the combustion chamber, allowing for high efficiency, or is bled overboard, allowing for higher power turbopumps.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The limited heat available to vaporize the fuel constrains engine power.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] A fuel- or oxidizer-rich mixture is burned in a preburner and then drives turbopumps, and this high-pressure exhaust is fed directly into the main chamber where the remainder of the fuel or oxidizer undergoes combustion, permitting very high pressures and efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Fuel- and oxidizer-rich mixtures are burned in separate preburners and drive the turbopumps, then both high-pressure exhausts, one oxygen rich and the other fuel rich, are fed directly into the main chamber where they combine and combust, permitting very high pressures and high efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Selecting an engine cycle is one of the earlier steps to rocket engine design.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Injectors are commonly laid out so that a fuel-rich layer is created at the combustion chamber wall.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] This reduces the temperature there, and downstream to the throat and even into the nozzle and permits the combustion chamber to be run at higher pressure, which permits a higher expansion ratio nozzle to be used which gives a higher *ISP* and better system performance.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] A liquid rocket engine often employs regenerative cooling, which uses the fuel or less commonly the oxidizer to cool the chamber and nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Ignition can be performed in many ways, but perhaps more so with liquid propellants than other rockets a consistent and significant ignitions source is required; a delay of ignition (in some cases as small as a few tens of milliseconds) can cause overpressure of the chamber due to excess propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] A hard start can even cause an engine to explode.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Generally, ignition systems try to apply flames across the injector surface, with a mass flow of approximately 1% of the full mass flow of the chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Safety interlocks are sometimes used to ensure the presence of an ignition source before the main valves open; however reliability of the interlocks can in some cases be lower than the ignition system.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Thus it depends on whether the system must fail safe, or whether overall mission success is more important.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Interlocks are rarely used for upper, uncrewed stages where failure of the interlock would cause loss of mission, but are present on the RS-25 engine, to shut the engines down prior to liftoff of the Space Shuttle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In addition, detection of successful ignition of the igniter is surprisingly difficult, some systems use thin wires that are cut by the flames, pressure sensors have also seen some use.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Methods of ignition include pyrotechnic, electrical (spark or hot wire), and chemical.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Hypergolic propellants have the advantage of self igniting, reliably and with less chance of hard starts.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In the 1940s, the Russians began to start engines with hypergols, to then switch over to the primary propellants after ignition.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] This was also used on the American F-1 rocket engine on the Apollo program.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Ignition with a pyrophoric agent: Triethylaluminium ignites on contact with air and will ignite and/or decompose on contact with water, and with any other oxidizer—it is one of the few substances sufficiently pyrophoric to ignite on contact with cryogenic liquid oxygen.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Its easy ignition makes it particularly desirable as a rocket engine ignitor.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] May be used in conjunction with triethylborane to create triethylaluminum-triethylborane, better known as TEA-TEB.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The idea of a liquid-fueled rocket as understood in the modern context first appeared in 1903 in the book *Exploration of the Universe with Rocket-Propelled Vehicles* by the Russian rocket scientist Konstantin Tsiolkovsky.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The magnitude of his contribution to astronautics is astounding, including the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation, multi-staged rockets, and using liquid oxygen and liquid hydrogen in liquid propellant rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Tsiolkovsky influenced later rocket scientists throughout Europe, like Wernher von Braun.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] From 1929 to 1930 in Leningrad Glushko pursued rocket research at the Gas Dynamics Laboratory (GDL), where a new research section was set up for the study of liquid-propellant and electric rocket engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] This resulted in the creation of ORM (from "Experimental Rocket Motor" in Russian) engines ORM-1 to ORM-52.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] A total of 100 bench tests of liquid-propellant rockets were conducted using various types of fuel, both low and high-boiling and thrust up to 300 kg was achieved.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] During this period in Moscow, Fredrich Tsander – a scientist and inventor – was designing and building liquid rocket engines which ran on compressed air and gasoline.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Tsander investigated high-energy fuels including powdered metals mixed with gasoline.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In September 1931 Tsander formed the Moscow based 'Group for the Study of Reactive Motion', better known by its Russian acronym "GIRD".
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In May 1932, Sergey Korolev replaced Tsander as the head of GIRD.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] On 17 August 1933, Mikhail Tikhonravov launched the first Soviet liquid-propelled rocket (the GIRD-9), fueled by liquid oxygen and jellied gasoline.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] It reached an altitude of 400 metres (1,300 ft).
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In January 1933 Tsander began development of the GIRD-X rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] This design burned liquid oxygen and gasoline and was one of the first engines to be regeneratively cooled by the liquid oxygen, which flowed around the inner wall of the combustion chamber before entering it.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Problems with burn-through during testing prompted a switch from gasoline to less energetic alcohol.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The final missile, 2.2 metres (7.2 ft) long by 140 millimetres (5.5 in) in diameter, had a mass of 30 kilograms (66 lb), and it was anticipated that it could carry a 2 kilograms (4.4 lb) payload to an altitude of 5.5 kilometres (3.4 mi).
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The GIRD X rocket was launched on 25 November 1933 and flew to a height of 80 meters.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In 1933 GDL and GIRD merged and became the Reactive Scientific Research Institute (RNII).
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] At RNII Gushko continued the development of liquid propellant rocket engines ОРМ-53 to ОРМ-102, with ORM-65 powering the RP-318 rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In 1938 Leonid Dushkin replaced Glushko and continued development of the ORM engines, including the engine for the rocket powered interceptor, the Bereznyak-Isayev BI-1.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] At RNII Tikhonravov worked on developing oxygen/alcohol liquid-propellant rocket engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Ultimately liquid propellant rocket engines were given a low priority during the late 1930s at RNII, however the research was productive and very important for later achievements of the Soviet rocket program.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Peruvian Pedro Paulet, who had experimented with rockets throughout his life in Peru, wrote a letter to *El Comercio* in Lima in 1927, claiming he had experimented with a liquid rocket engine while he was a student in Paris three decades earlier.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Historians of early rocketry experiments, among them Max Valier, Willy Ley, and John D.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Clark, have given differing amounts of credence to Paulet's report.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Valier applauded Paulet's liquid-propelled rocket design in the Verein für Raumschiffahrt publication *Die Rakete*, saying the engine had "amazing power" and that his plans were necessary for future rocket development.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Hermann Oberth would name Paulet as a pioneer in rocketry in 1965.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Wernher von Braun would also describe Paulet as "the pioneer of the liquid fuel propulsion motor" and stated that "Paulet helped man reach the Moon".
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Paulet was later approached by Nazi Germany, being invited to join the Astronomische Gesellschaft to help develop rocket technology, though he refused to assist after discovering that the project was destined for weaponization and never shared the formula for his propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] According to filmmaker and researcher Álvaro Mejía, Frederick I.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Ordway III would later attempt to discredit Paulet's discoveries in the context of the Cold War and in an effort to shift the public image of von Braun away from his history with Nazi Germany.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The first *flight* of a liquid-propellant rocket took place on March 16, 1926 at Auburn, Massachusetts, when American professor Dr.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Goddard launched a vehicle using liquid oxygen and gasoline as propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The rocket, which was dubbed "Nell", rose just 41 feet during a 2.5-second flight that ended in a cabbage field, but it was an important demonstration that rockets using liquid propulsion were possible.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Goddard proposed liquid propellants about fifteen years earlier and began to seriously experiment with them in 1921.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The German-Romanian Hermann Oberth published a book in 1923 suggesting the use of liquid propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In Germany, engineers and scientists became enthralled with liquid propulsion, building and testing them in the late 1920s within Opel RAK, the world's first rocket program, in Rüsselsheim.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] According to Max Valier's account, Opel RAK rocket designer, Friedrich Wilhelm Sander launched two liquid-fuel rockets at Opel Rennbahn in Rüsselsheim on April 10 and April 12, 1929.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] These Opel RAK rockets have been the first European, and after Goddard the world's second, liquid-fuel rockets in history.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In his book "Raketenfahrt" Valier describes the size of the rockets as of 21 cm in diameter and with a length of 74 cm, weighing 7 kg empty and 16 kg with fuel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The maximum thrust was 45 to 50 kp, with a total burning time of 132 seconds.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] These properties indicate a gas pressure pumping.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The main purpose of these tests was to develop the liquid rocket-propulsion system for a Gebrüder-Müller-Griessheim aircraft under construction for a planned flight across the English channel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Winter, curator at National Air and Space Museum in Washington, DC, confirms the Opel group was working, in addition to their solid-fuel rockets used for land-speed records and the world's first crewed rocket-plane flights with the Opel RAK.1, on liquid-fuel rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The Great Depression brought an end to the Opel RAK activities.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] After working for the German military in the early 1930s, Sander was arrested by Gestapo in 1935, when private rocket-engineering became forbidden in Germany.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] He was convicted of treason to 5 years in prison and forced to sell his company, he died in 1938.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Max Valier was a co-founder of an amateur research group, the VfR, working on liquid rockets in the early 1930s, and many of whose members eventually became important rocket technology pioneers, including Wernher von Braun.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Von Braun served as head of the army research station that designed the V-2 rocket weapon for the Nazis.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] By the late 1930s, use of rocket propulsion for crewed flight began to be seriously experimented with, as Germany's Heinkel He 176 made the first crewed rocket-powered flight using a liquid rocket engine, designed by German aeronautics engineer Hellmuth Walter on June 20, 1939.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The only production rocket-powered combat aircraft ever to see military service, the Me 163 *Komet* in 1944-45, also used a Walter-designed liquid rocket engine, the Walter HWK 109-509, which produced up to 1,700 kgf (16.7 kN) thrust at full power.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] After World War II the American government and military finally seriously considered liquid-propellant rockets as weapons and began to fund work on them.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] The Soviet Union did likewise, and thus began the Space Race.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] In 2010s 3D printed engines started being used for spaceflight.
[src:rocket-propulsion/liquid-propellant-rocket] Examples of such engines include SuperDraco used in launch escape system of the SpaceX Dragon 2 and also engines used for first or second stages in launch vehicles from Astra, Orbex, Relativity Space, Skyrora, or Launcher.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] A **nozzle** is a device designed to control the direction or characteristics of a fluid flow (specially to increase velocity) as it exits (or enters) an enclosed chamber or pipe.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] A nozzle is often a pipe or tube of varying cross sectional area, and it can be used to direct or modify the flow of a fluid (liquid or gas).
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Nozzles are frequently used to control the rate of flow, speed, direction, mass, shape, and/or the pressure of the stream that emerges from them.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] In a nozzle, the velocity of fluid increases at the expense of its pressure energy.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] A **gas jet**, **fluid jet**, or **hydro jet** is a nozzle intended to eject fluid in a coherent stream into a surrounding medium.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Gas jets are commonly found in gas stoves, ovens, or barbecues.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Gas jets were commonly used for light before the development of electric light.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Other types of fluid jets are found in carburetors, where smooth calibrated orifices are used to regulate the flow of fuel into an engine, and in jacuzzis or spas.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Another specialized jet is the laminar jet.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] This is a water jet that contains devices to smooth out the pressure and flow, and produces laminar flow, as its name suggests.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] This provides better results for fountains.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] The foam jet is another type of jet, which uses foam instead of a gas or fluid.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Nozzles used for feeding hot blast into a blast furnace or forge are called tuyeres.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Jet nozzles are also used in large rooms where the distribution of air via ceiling diffusers is not possible or not practical.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Diffusers that uses jet nozzles are called jet diffuser where it will be arranged in the side wall areas in order to distribute air.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] When the temperature difference between the supply air and the room air changes, the supply air stream is deflected upwards, to supply warm air, or downwards, to supply cold air.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Frequently, the goal of a nozzle is to increase the kinetic energy of the flowing medium at the expense of its pressure and internal energy.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Nozzles can be described as *convergent* (narrowing down from a wide diameter to a smaller diameter in the direction of the flow) or *divergent* (expanding from a smaller diameter to a larger one).
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] A de Laval nozzle has a convergent section followed by a divergent section and is often called a *convergent–divergent* (*CD*, *con–di*) nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Convergent nozzles accelerate subsonic fluids.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] If the nozzle pressure ratio is high enough, then the flow will reach sonic velocity at the narrowest point (i.e. the *nozzle throat*).
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] In this situation, the nozzle is said to be *choked*.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Increasing the nozzle pressure ratio further will not increase the throat Mach number above one.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Downstream (i.e. external to the nozzle) the flow is free to expand to supersonic velocities; however, Mach 1 can be a very high speed for a hot gas because the speed of sound varies as the square root of absolute temperature.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] This fact is used extensively in rocketry, where hypersonic flows are required and where propellant mixtures are deliberately chosen to further increase the sonic speed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Divergent nozzles slow fluids if the flow is subsonic, but they accelerate sonic or supersonic fluids.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Convergent–divergent nozzles can therefore accelerate fluids that have choked in the convergent section to supersonic speeds.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] This CD process is more efficient than allowing a convergent nozzle to expand supersonically externally.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] The shape of the divergent section also ensures that the direction of the escaping gases is directly backwards, as any sideways component would not contribute to thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] A jet exhaust produces thrust from the energy obtained from burning fuel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] The hot gas is at a higher pressure than the outside air and escapes from the engine through a *propelling nozzle*, which increases the speed of the gas.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Exhaust speed needs to be faster than the aircraft speed in order to produce thrust but an excessive speed difference wastes fuel (poor propulsive efficiency).
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Jet engines for subsonic flight use convergent nozzles with a sonic exit velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Engines for supersonic flight, such as used for fighters and SST aircraft (e.g.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Concorde) achieve the high exhaust speeds necessary for supersonic flight by using a divergent extension to the convergent engine nozzle which accelerates the exhaust to supersonic speeds.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Rocket motors maximise thrust and exhaust velocity by using convergent–divergent nozzles with very large area ratios and therefore extremely high pressure ratios.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Mass flow is at a premium because all the propulsive mass is carried with the vehicle, and very high exhaust speeds are desirable.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Magnetic nozzles have also been proposed for some types of propulsion, such as VASIMR, in which the flow of plasma is directed by magnetic fields instead of walls made of solid matter.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Many nozzles produce a very fine spray of liquids.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Vacuum cleaner nozzles come in several different shapes.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Vacuum nozzles are used in vacuum cleaners.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] Some nozzles are shaped to produce a stream that is of a particular shape.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] For example, extrusion molding is a way of producing lengths of metals or plastics or other materials with a particular cross-section.
[src:rocket-propulsion/nozzle] This nozzle is typically referred to as a die.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] A **rocket engine**, also known as a **rocket motor**, is a reaction engine, producing thrust in accordance with Newton's third law by ejecting reaction mass rearward, usually a high-speed jet of high-temperature gas produced by the combustion of rocket propellant stored inside the rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] However, non-combusting forms such as cold gas thrusters, nuclear thermal rockets, and ion engines exist.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket vehicles carry their own oxidiser, unlike most combustion engines such as pulse engines or jet engines, so rocket engines can be used in a vacuum, and they can achieve great speed, beyond escape velocity if enough delta V is supplied.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Vehicles commonly propelled by rocket engines include missiles, artillery shells, ballistic missiles, and spaceships.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Compared to other types of jet engines, rocket engines typically have the highest thrust, but are the least propellant-efficient (they have the lowest specific impulse).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For thermal rockets, pure hydrogen, the lightest of all elements, gives the highest exhaust velocity, but practical chemical rockets produce a mix of heavier species, reducing the exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Here, "rocket" is used as an abbreviation for "rocket engine".
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket engines produce thrust by the expulsion of gas that has been accelerated to high speed through a nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The fluid is usually a gas created by high pressure (150-to-4,350-pound-per-square-inch (10 to 300 bar)) combustion of solid or liquid propellants, consisting of fuel and oxidiser components, within a combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] As the gases expand through the nozzle, they are accelerated to very high (supersonic) speed, and the reaction to this pushes the vehicle (rocket) in the opposite direction.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Combustion is most frequently used for practical rockets, as the laws of thermodynamics (more specifically Carnot's theorem) dictate that high temperatures and pressures are desirable for the best thermal efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Nuclear thermal rockets are capable of higher efficiencies, but have low thrust, thanks to the low mass of the propellants used, and also have environmental problems which preclude their routine use in the Earth's atmosphere and cislunar space.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For model rocketry, an available alternative to combustion is a water rocket pressurized by compressed air, carbon dioxide, nitrogen, or any other readily available, inert gas.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket propellant is mass that is stored, usually in some form of tank, or within the combustion chamber itself, prior to being ejected from a rocket engine in the form of a fluid jet to produce thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Chemical rocket propellants are the most commonly used.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] These undergo exothermic chemical reactions producing a hot jet of gas for propulsion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Alternatively, a chemically inert reaction mass can be heated by a high-energy power source through a heat exchanger in lieu of a combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Solid rocket propellants are prepared in a mixture of fuel and oxidising components called *grain*, and the propellant storage casing effectively becomes the combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Liquid-fueled rockets force separate fuel and oxidizer components into the combustion chamber, where they mix and burn.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Hybrid rocket engines use a combination of solid and liquid or gaseous propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Both liquid and hybrid rockets use *injectors* to introduce the propellant into the chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] These are often an array of simple jets – holes through which the propellant escapes under pressure; but sometimes may be more complex spray nozzles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] When two or more propellants are injected, the jets usually deliberately cause the propellants to collide as this breaks up the flow into smaller droplets that burn more easily.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For chemical rockets the combustion chamber is typically cylindrical, and flame holders, used to hold a part of the combustion in a slower-flowing portion of the combustion chamber, are not needed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The dimensions of the cylinder are such that the propellant is able to combust thoroughly; different rocket propellants require different combustion chamber sizes for this to occur.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] L* is typically in the range of 64–152 centimetres (25–60 in).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The temperatures and pressures typically reached in a rocket combustion chamber in order to achieve practical thermal efficiency are extreme compared to a non-afterburning airbreathing jet engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] No atmospheric nitrogen is present to dilute and cool the combustion, so the propellant mixture can reach true stoichiometric ratios.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This, in combination with the high pressures, means that the rate of heat conduction through the walls is very high.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In order for fuel and oxidiser to flow into the chamber, the pressure of the propellants entering the combustion chamber must exceed the pressure inside the combustion chamber itself.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This may be accomplished by a variety of design approaches including turbopumps or, in simpler engines, via sufficient tank pressure to advance fluid flow.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The hot gas produced in the combustion chamber is permitted to escape through a narrow space, called the throat, to increase the velocity until it reaches Mach 1, and then continues to accelerate through a diverging expansion section.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] When sufficient pressure is provided to the nozzle (about 2.5–3 times ambient pressure), the nozzle *chokes* and a supersonic jet is formed, dramatically accelerating the gas, converting most of the thermal energy into kinetic energy.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Exhaust speeds vary, depending on the expansion ratio the nozzle is designed for, but exhaust speeds as high as ten times the speed of sound in air at sea level are not uncommon.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] About half of the rocket engine's thrust comes from the unbalanced pressures inside the combustion chamber, and the rest comes from the pressures acting against the inside of the nozzle (see diagram).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] As the gas expands (adiabatically) the pressure against the nozzle's walls forces the rocket engine in one direction while accelerating the gas in the other.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The most commonly used nozzle is the de Laval nozzle, a fixed geometry nozzle with a high expansion-ratio.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The large bell- or cone-shaped nozzle extension beyond the throat gives the rocket engine its characteristic shape.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The exit static pressure of the exhaust jet depends on the chamber pressure and the ratio of exit to throat area of the nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In practice, perfect expansion is only achievable with a variable–exit-area nozzle (since ambient pressure decreases as altitude increases), and is not possible above a certain altitude as ambient pressure approaches zero.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] If the nozzle is not perfectly expanded, then loss of efficiency occurs.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Grossly over-expanded nozzles lose less efficiency, but can cause mechanical problems with the nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Fixed-area nozzles become progressively more under-expanded as they gain altitude.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Almost all de Laval nozzles will be momentarily grossly over-expanded during startup in an atmosphere.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] To maintain this ideal of equality between the exhaust's exit pressure and the ambient pressure, the diameter of the nozzle would need to increase with altitude, giving the pressure a longer nozzle to act on (and reducing the exit pressure and temperature).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This increase is difficult to arrange in a lightweight fashion, although is routinely done with other forms of jet engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In rocketry a lightweight compromise nozzle is generally used and some reduction in atmospheric performance occurs when used at other than the 'design altitude' or when throttled.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] When exhausting into a sufficiently low ambient pressure (vacuum) several issues arise.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] One is the sheer weight of the nozzle—beyond a certain point, for a particular vehicle, the extra weight of the nozzle outweighs any performance gained.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Secondly, as the exhaust gases adiabatically expand within the nozzle they cool, and eventually some of the chemicals can freeze, producing 'snow' within the jet.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This causes instabilities in the jet and must be avoided.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] On a De Laval nozzle, exhaust gas flow detachment will occur in a grossly over-expanded nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] As the detachment point will not be uniform around the axis of the engine, a side force may be imparted to the engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This side force may change over time and result in control problems with the launch vehicle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Advanced altitude-compensating designs, such as the aerospike or plug nozzle, attempt to minimize performance losses by adjusting to varying expansion ratio caused by changing altitude.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For a rocket engine to be propellant efficient, it is important that the maximum pressures possible be created on the walls of the chamber and nozzle by a specific amount of propellant; as this is the source of the thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] However, speed is significantly affected by all three of the above factors and the exhaust speed is an excellent measure of the engine propellant efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This is termed *exhaust velocity*, and after allowance is made for factors that can reduce it, the **effective exhaust velocity** is one of the most important parameters of a rocket engine (although weight, cost, ease of manufacture etc. are usually also very important).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For aerodynamic reasons the flow goes sonic ("chokes") at the narrowest part of the nozzle, the 'throat'.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Since the speed of sound in gases increases with the square root of temperature, the use of hot exhaust gas greatly improves performance.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Expansion in the rocket nozzle then further multiplies the speed, typically between 1.5 and 2 times, giving a highly collimated hypersonic exhaust jet.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The speed increase of a rocket nozzle is mostly determined by its area expansion ratio—the ratio of the area of the exit to the area of the throat, but detailed properties of the gas are also important.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Larger ratio nozzles are more massive but are able to extract more heat from the combustion gases, increasing the exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Vehicles typically require the overall thrust to change direction over the length of the burn.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rockets can be further optimised to even more extreme performance along one or more of these axes at the expense of the others.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The most important metric for the efficiency of a rocket engine is impulse per unit of propellant, this is called specific impulse (usually written $I_{sp}$ ).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This is either measured as a speed (the *effective exhaust velocity* $v_{e}$ in metres/second or ft/s) or as a time (seconds).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For example, if an engine producing 100 pounds of thrust runs for 320 seconds and burns 100 pounds of propellant, then the specific impulse is 320 seconds.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The higher the specific impulse, the less propellant is required to provide the desired impulse.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The specific impulse that can be achieved is primarily a function of the propellant mix (and ultimately would limit the specific impulse), but practical limits on chamber pressures and the nozzle expansion ratios reduce the performance that can be achieved.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Since, unlike a jet engine, a conventional rocket motor lacks an air intake, there is no 'ram drag' to deduct from the gross thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Consequently, the net thrust of a rocket motor is equal to the gross thrust (apart from static back pressure).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The ${\dot {m}}\;v_{e-opt}\,$ term represents the momentum thrust, which remains constant at a given throttle setting, whereas the $A_{e}(p_{e}-p_{amb})\,$ term represents the pressure thrust term.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] At full throttle, the net thrust of a rocket motor improves slightly with increasing altitude, because as atmospheric pressure decreases with altitude, the pressure thrust term increases.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] At the surface of the Earth the pressure thrust may be reduced by up to 30%, depending on the engine design.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This reduction drops roughly exponentially to zero with increasing altitude.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Maximum efficiency for a rocket engine is achieved by maximising the momentum contribution of the equation without incurring penalties from over expanding the exhaust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Since ambient pressure changes with altitude, most rocket engines spend very little time operating at peak efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Since specific impulse is force divided by the rate of mass flow, this equation means that the specific impulse varies with altitude.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Due to the specific impulse varying with pressure, a quantity that is easy to compare and calculate with is useful.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rockets can be throttled by controlling the propellant combustion rate ${\dot {m}}$ (usually measured in kg/s or lb/s).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In liquid and hybrid rockets, the propellant flow entering the chamber is controlled using valves, in solid rockets it is controlled by changing the area of propellant that is burning and this can be designed into the propellant grain (and hence cannot be controlled in real-time).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rockets can usually be throttled down to an exit pressure of about one-third of ambient pressure (often limited by flow separation in nozzles) and up to a maximum limit determined only by the mechanical strength of the engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For example, some more recent liquid-propellant engine designs that have been optimised for greater throttling capability (BE-3, Raptor) can be throttled to as low as 18–20 per cent of rated thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Solid rockets can be throttled by using shaped grains that will vary their surface area over the course of the burn.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket engine nozzles are surprisingly efficient heat engines for generating a high speed jet, as a consequence of the high combustion temperature and high compression ratio.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket nozzles give an excellent approximation to adiabatic expansion which is a reversible process, and hence they give efficiencies which are very close to that of the Carnot cycle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Given the temperatures reached, over 60% efficiency can be achieved with chemical rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For a *vehicle* employing a rocket engine the energetic efficiency is very good if the vehicle speed approaches or somewhat exceeds the exhaust velocity (relative to launch); but at low speeds the energy efficiency goes to 0% at zero speed (as with all jet propulsion).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] See Rocket energy efficiency for more details.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rockets, of all the jet engines, indeed of essentially all engines, have the highest thrust-to-weight ratio.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This is especially true for liquid-fueled rocket engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This high performance is due to the small volume of pressure vessels that make up the engine—the pumps, pipes and combustion chambers involved.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The lack of inlet duct and the use of dense liquid propellant allows the pressurisation system to be small and lightweight, whereas duct engines have to deal with air which has around three orders of magnitude lower density.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Of the liquid fuels used, density is lowest for liquid hydrogen.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket combustion chambers are normally operated at fairly high pressure, typically 10–200 bar (1–20 MPa, 150–3,000 psi).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] When operated within significant atmospheric pressure, higher combustion chamber pressures give better performance by permitting a larger and more efficient nozzle to be fitted without it being grossly overexpanded.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] However, these high pressures cause the outermost part of the chamber to be under very large hoop stresses – rocket engines are pressure vessels.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Worse, due to the high temperatures created in rocket engines the materials used tend to have a significantly lowered working tensile strength.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In addition, significant temperature gradients are set up in the walls of the chamber and nozzle, these cause differential expansion of the inner liner that create internal stresses.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] A **hard start** refers to an over-pressure condition during start of a rocket engine at ignition.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In the worst cases, this takes the form of an unconfined explosion, resulting in the damage or destruction of the engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket fuels, hypergolic or otherwise, must be introduced into the combustion chamber at the correct rate in order to have a controlled rate of production of hot gas.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] A "hard start" indicates that the quantity of combustible propellant that entered the combustion chamber prior to ignition was too large.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The result is an excessive spike of pressure, possibly leading to structural failure or explosion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Avoiding hard starts involves careful timing of the ignition relative to valve timing or varying the mixture ratio so as to limit the maximum pressure that can occur or simply ensuring an adequate ignition source is present well prior to propellant entering the chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Explosions from hard starts usually cannot happen with purely gaseous propellants, since the amount of the gas present in the chamber is limited by the injector area relative to the throat area, and for practical designs, propellant mass escapes too quickly to be an issue.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] A famous example of a hard start was the explosion of Wernher von Braun's "1W" engine during a demonstration to General Walter Dornberger on December 21, 1932.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Delayed ignition allowed the chamber to fill with alcohol and liquid oxygen, which exploded violently.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Shrapnel was embedded in the walls, but nobody was hit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The extreme vibration and acoustic environment inside a rocket motor commonly result in peak stresses well above mean values, especially in the presence of organ pipe-like resonances and gas turbulence.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The combustion may display undesired instabilities, of sudden or periodic nature.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This may lead to high-amplitude pressure oscillations, often in ultrasonic range, which may damage the motor.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Oscillations of ±200 psi at 25 kHz were the cause of failures of early versions of the Titan II missile second stage engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The other failure mode is a deflagration to detonation transition; the supersonic pressure wave formed in the combustion chamber may destroy the engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Combustion instability was also a problem during Atlas development.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The Rocketdyne engines used in the Atlas family were found to suffer from this effect in several static firing tests, and three missile launches exploded on the pad due to rough combustion in the booster engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In most cases, it occurred while attempting to start the engines with a "dry start" method whereby the igniter mechanism would be activated prior to propellant injection.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] During the process of man-rating Atlas for Project Mercury, solving combustion instability was a high priority, and the final two Mercury flights sported an upgraded propulsion system with baffled injectors and a hypergolic igniter.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The problem affecting Atlas vehicles was mainly the so-called "racetrack" phenomenon, where burning propellant would swirl around in a circle at faster and faster speeds, eventually producing vibration strong enough to rupture the engine, leading to complete destruction of the rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] It was eventually solved by adding several baffles around the injector face to break up swirling propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] More significantly, combustion instability was a problem with the Saturn F-1 engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Some of the early units tested exploded during static firing, which led to the addition of injector baffles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In the Soviet space program, combustion instability also proved a problem on some rocket engines, including the RD-107 engine used in the R-7 family and the RD-216 used in the R-14 family, and several failures of these vehicles occurred before the problem was solved.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Soviet engineering and manufacturing processes never satisfactorily resolved combustion instability in larger RP-1/LOX engines, so the RD-171 engine used to power the Zenit family still used four smaller thrust chambers fed by a common engine mechanism.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The combustion instabilities can be provoked by remains of cleaning solvents in the engine (e.g. the first attempted launch of a Titan II in 1962), reflected shock wave, initial instability after ignition, explosion near the nozzle that reflects into the combustion chamber, and many more factors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In stable engine designs the oscillations are quickly suppressed; in unstable designs they persist for prolonged periods.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Oscillation suppressors are commonly used.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] A low frequency oscillation in chamber pressure below 200 Hertz.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Usually it is caused by pressure variations in feed lines due to variations in acceleration of the vehicle, when rocket engines are building up thrust, are shut down or are being throttled.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Chugging can cause a worsening feedback loop, as cyclic variation in thrust causes longitudinal vibrations to travel up the rocket, causing the fuel lines to vibrate, which in turn do not deliver propellant smoothly into the engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This phenomenon is known as "pogo oscillations" or "pogo", named after the pogo stick.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In the worst case, this may result in damage to the payload or vehicle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Chugging can be minimised by using several methods, such as installing energy-absorbing devices on feed lines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] An intermediate frequency oscillation in chamber pressure between 200 and 1000 Hertz.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Usually caused due to insufficient pressure drop across the injectors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] It generally is mostly annoying, rather than being damaging.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Buzzing is known to have adverse effects on engine performance and reliability, primarily as it causes material fatigue.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In extreme cases combustion can end up being forced backwards through the injectors – this can cause explosions with monopropellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] A high frequency oscillation in chamber pressure above 1000 Hertz, sometimes called screaming or squealing.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The most immediately damaging, and the hardest to control.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Acoustic oscillations can be excited by thermal processes, such as the flow of hot air through a pipe or combustion in a chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Specifically, standing acoustic waves inside a chamber can be intensified if combustion occurs more intensely in regions where the pressure of the acoustic wave is maximal.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Such effects are very difficult to predict analytically during the design process, and have usually been addressed by expensive, time-consuming and extensive testing, combined with trial and error remedial correction measures.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Screeching is often dealt with by detailed changes to injectors, changes in the propellant chemistry, vaporising the propellant before injection or use of Helmholtz dampers within the combustion chambers to change the resonant modes of the chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For all but the very smallest sizes, rocket exhaust compared to other engines is generally very noisy.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] As the hypersonic exhaust mixes with the ambient air, shock waves are formed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The Space Shuttle generated over 200 dB(A) of noise around its base.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] To reduce this, and the risk of payload damage or injury to the crew atop the stack, the mobile launcher platform was fitted with a Sound Suppression System that sprayed 1.1 million litres (290,000 US gal) of water around the base of the rocket in 41 seconds at launch time.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Using this system kept sound levels within the payload bay to 142 dB.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The sound intensity from the shock waves generated depends on the size of the rocket and on the exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Such shock waves seem to account for the characteristic crackling and popping sounds produced by large rocket engines when heard live.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] These noise peaks typically overload microphones and audio electronics, and so are generally weakened or entirely absent in recorded or broadcast audio reproductions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For large rockets at close range, the acoustic effects could actually kill.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] More worryingly for space agencies, such sound levels can also damage the launch structure, or worse, be reflected back at the comparatively delicate rocket above.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This is why so much water is typically used at launches.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The water spray changes the acoustic qualities of the air and reduces or deflects the sound energy away from the rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Generally speaking, noise is most intense when a rocket is close to the ground, since the noise from the engines radiates up away from the jet, as well as reflecting off the ground.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Also, when the vehicle is moving slowly, little of the chemical energy input to the engine can go into increasing the kinetic energy of the rocket (since useful power *P* transmitted to the vehicle is $P=F*V$ for thrust *F* and speed *V*).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Then the largest portion of the energy is dissipated in the exhaust's interaction with the ambient air, producing noise.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This noise can be reduced somewhat by flame trenches with roofs, by water injection around the jet and by deflecting the jet at an angle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The development of the US rocket engine industry has been shaped by a complex web of relationships between government agencies, private companies, research institutions, and other stakeholders.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Since the establishment of the first liquid-propellant rocket engine company (Reaction Motors, Inc.) in 1941 and the first government laboratory (GALCIT) devoted to the subject, the US liquid-propellant rocket engine (LPRE) industry has undergone significant changes.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] At least 14 US companies have been involved in the design, development, manufacture, testing, and flight support operations of various types of rocket engines from 1940 to 2000.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In contrast to other countries like Russia, China, or India, where only government or pseudogovernment organisations engage in this business, the US government relies heavily on private industry.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] These commercial companies are essential to the continued viability of the United States and its form of governance, as they compete with one another to provide cutting-edge rocket engines that meet the needs of the government, the military, and the private sector.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In the United States the company that develops the LPRE usually is awarded the production contract.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Generally, the need or demand for a new rocket engine comes from government agencies such as NASA or the Department of Defense.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Once the need is identified, government agencies may issue requests for proposals (RFPs) to solicit proposals from private companies and research institutions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Private companies and research institutions, in turn, may invest in research and development (R&D) activities to develop new rocket engine technologies that meet the needs and specifications outlined in the RFPs.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Alongside private companies, universities, independent research institutes and government laboratories also play a critical role in the research and development of rocket engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Universities provide graduate and undergraduate education to train qualified technical personnel, and their research programs often contribute to the advancement of rocket engine technologies.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] More than 25 universities in the US have taught or are currently teaching courses related to Liquid Propellant Rocket Engines (LPREs), and their graduate and undergraduate education programs are considered one of their most important contributions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Universities such as Princeton University, Cornell University, Purdue University, Pennsylvania State University, University of Alabama, the Navy's Post-Graduate School, or the California Institute of Technology have conducted excellent R&D work on topics related to the rocket engine industry.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] One of the earliest examples of the contribution of universities to the rocket engine industry is the work of the GALCIT in 1941.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] They demonstrated the first jet-assisted takeoff (JATO) rockets to the Army, leading to the establishment of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] However the transfer of knowledge from research professors and their projects to the rocket engine industry has been a mixed experience.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] While some notable professors and relevant research projects have positively influenced industry practices and understanding of LPREs, the connection between university research and commercial companies has been inconsistent and weak.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Universities were not always aware of the industry's specific needs, and engineers and designers in the industry had limited knowledge of university research.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] As a result, many university research programs remained relatively unknown to industry decision-makers.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Furthermore, in the last few decades, certain university research projects, while interesting to professors, were not useful to the industry due to a lack of communication or relevance to industry needs.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Government laboratories, including the Rocket Propulsion Laboratory (now part of Air Force Research Laboratory), Arnold Engineering Test Center, NASA Marshall Space Flight Center, Jet Propulsion Laboratory, Stennis Space Center, White Sands Proving Grounds, and NASA John H.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Glenn Research Center, have played crucial roles in the development of liquid rocket propulsion engines (LPREs).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] They have conducted unbiased testing, guided work at US and some non-US contractors, performed research and development, and provided essential testing facilities including hover test facilities and simulated altitude test facilities and resources.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Initially, private companies or foundations financed smaller test facilities, but since the 1950s, the U.S. government has funded larger test facilities at government laboratories.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This approach reduced costs for the government by not building similar facilities at contractors' plants but increased complexity and expenses for contractors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Nonetheless, government laboratories have solidified their significance and contributed to LPRE advancements.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] LPRE programs have been subject to several cancellations in the United States, even after spending millions of dollars on their development.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For example, the M-l LOX/LH2 LPRE, Titan I, and the RS-2200 aerospike, as well as several JATO units and large uncooled thrust chambers were cancelled.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The cancellations of these programs were not related to the specific LPRE's performance or any issues with it.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Instead, they were due to the cancellation of the vehicle programs the engine was intended for or budget cuts imposed by the government.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Russia and the former Soviet Union was and still is the world's foremost nation in developing and building rocket engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] From 1950 to 1998, their organisations developed, built, and put into operation a larger number and a larger variety of liquid propellant rocket engine (LPRE) designs than any other country.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Approximately 500 different LPREs have been developed before 2003.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For comparison the United States has developed slightly more than 300 (before 2003).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The Soviets also had the most rocket-propelled flight vehicles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] They had more liquid propellant ballistic missiles and more space launch vehicles derived or converted from these decommissioned ballistic missiles than any other nation.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] As of the end of 1998, the Russians (or earlier the Soviet Union) had successfully launched 2573 satellites with LPREs or almost 65% of the world total of 3973.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] All of these vehicle flights were made possible by the timely development of suitable high-performance reliable LPREs.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Unlike many other countries where the development and production of rocket engines were consolidated within a single organisation, the Soviet Union took a different approach, they established numerous specialised design bureaus (DB) which would compete for development contracts.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Design bureaus which specialised in rocket engines often possessed the necessary personnel, facilities, and equipment to conduct laboratory tests, flow tests, and ground testing of experimental rocket engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Some even had specialised facilities for testing very large engines, conducting static firings of engines installed in vehicle stages, or simulating altitude conditions during engine tests.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] In certain cases, engine testing, certification and quality control were outsourced to other organisations and locations with more suitable test facilities.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Many DBs also had housing complexes, gymnasiums, and medical facilities intended to support the needs of their employees and their families.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The Soviet Union's LPRE development effort saw significant growth during the 1960s and reached its peak in the 1970s.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This era coincided with the Cold War between the Soviet Union and the United States, characterised by intense competition in spaceflight achievements.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Between 14 and 17 Design Bureaus and research institutes were actively involved in developing LPREs during this period.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] These organisations received relatively steady support and funding due to high military and spaceflight priorities, which facilitated the continuous development of new engine concepts and manufacturing methods.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Once a mission with a new vehicle (missile or spacecraft) was established it was passed on to a design bureau whose role was to oversee the development of the entire rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This meant that the development or design study of a rocket engine was always aimed at a specific application which entailed set requirements.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] When it comes to which DBs were awarded contracts for the development of new rocket engines either a single design bureau would be chosen or several design bureaus would be given the same contract which sometimes led to fierce competition between DBs.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] When only one DB was picked for the development, it was often the result of the relationship between a vehicle or system's chief designer and the chief designer of a rocket engine specialised DB.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] If the vehicle's chief designer was happy with previous work done by a certain design bureau it was not unusual to see continued reliance on that LPRE bureau for that class of engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] For example, all but one of the LPREs for submarine-launched missiles were developed by the same design bureau for the same vehicle development prime contractor.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] However, when two parallel engine development programs were supported in order to select the superior one for a specific application, several qualified rocket engine models were never used.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This luxury of choice was not commonly available in other nations.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] However, the use of design bureaus also led to certain issues, including program cancellations and duplication.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Some major programs were cancelled, resulting in the disposal or storage of previously developed engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] One notable example of duplication and cancellation was the development of engines for the R-9A ballistic missile.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Two sets of engines were supported, but ultimately only one set was selected, leaving several perfectly functional engines unused.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Similarly, for the ambitious heavy N-l space launch vehicle intended for lunar and planetary missions, the Soviet Union developed and put into production at least two engines for each of the six stages.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Additionally, they developed alternate engines for a more advanced N-l vehicle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] However, the program faced multiple flight failures, and with the United States' successful Moon landing, the program was ultimately cancelled, leaving the Soviet Union with a surplus of newly qualified engines without a clear purpose.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] These examples demonstrate the complex dynamics and challenges faced by the Soviet Union in managing the development and production of rocket engines through Design Bureaus.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The development of rocket engines in the Soviet Union was marked by significant achievements, but it also carried ethical considerations due to numerous accidents and fatalities.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] From a Science and Technology Studies point of view, the ethical implications of these incidents shed light on the complex relationship between technology, human factors, and the prioritisation of scientific advancement over safety.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The Soviet Union encountered a series of tragic accidents and mishaps in the development and operation of rocket engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Notably, the USSR holds the unfortunate distinction of having experienced more injuries and deaths resulting from liquid propellant rocket engine (LPRE) accidents than any other country.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] These incidents brought into question the ethical considerations surrounding the development, testing, and operational use of rocket engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] One of the most notable disasters occurred in 1960 when the R-16 ballistic missile suffered a catastrophic accident on the launchpad at the Tyuratam launch facility.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This incident resulted in the deaths of 124 engineers and military personnel, including Marshal M.I.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] Nedelin, a former deputy minister of defence.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The explosion occurred after the second-stage rocket engine suddenly ignited, causing the fully loaded missile to disintegrate.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The explosion resulted from the ignition and explosion of the mixed hypergolic propellants, consisting of nitric acid with additives and UDMH (unsymmetrical dimethylhydrazine).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] While the immediate cause of the 1960 accident was attributed to a lack of protective circuits in the missile control unit, the ethical considerations surrounding LPRE accidents in the USSR extend beyond specific technical failures.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The secrecy surrounding these accidents, which remained undisclosed for approximately three decades, raises concerns about transparency, accountability, and the protection of human life.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The decision to keep fatal LPRE accidents hidden from the public eye reflects a broader ethical dilemma.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] The Soviet government, driven by the pursuit of scientific and technological superiority during the Cold War, sought to maintain an image of invincibility and conceal the failures that accompanied their advancements.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p01] This prioritisation of national prestige over the well-being and safety of workers raises questions about the ethical responsibility of the state and the organisations involved.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket engines are usually statically tested at a test facility before being put into production.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] For high altitude engines, either a shorter nozzle must be used, or the rocket must be tested in a large vacuum chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket vehicles have a reputation for unreliability and danger; especially catastrophic failures.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Contrary to this reputation, carefully designed rockets can be made arbitrarily reliable.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] In military use, rockets are not unreliable.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] However, one of the main non-military uses of rockets is for orbital launch.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] In this application, the premium has typically been placed on minimum weight, and it is difficult to achieve high reliability and low weight simultaneously.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] In addition, if the number of flights launched is low, there is a very high chance of a design, operations or manufacturing error causing destruction of the vehicle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The Rocketdyne H-1 engine, used in a cluster of eight in the first stage of the Saturn I and Saturn IB launch vehicles, had no catastrophic failures in 152 engine-flights.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The Pratt and Whitney RL10 engine, used in a cluster of six in the Saturn I second stage, had no catastrophic failures in 36 engine-flights.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The Rocketdyne F-1 engine, used in a cluster of five in the first stage of the Saturn V, had no failures in 65 engine-flights.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The Rocketdyne J-2 engine, used in a cluster of five in the Saturn V second stage, and singly in the Saturn IB second stage and Saturn V third stage, had no catastrophic failures in 86 engine-flights.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Booster, used in pairs, caused one notable catastrophic failure in 270 engine-flights.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The RS-25, used in a cluster of three, flew in 46 refurbished engine units.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] These made a total of 405 engine-flights with no catastrophic in-flight failures.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] A single in-flight RS-25 engine failure occurred during Space Shuttle *Challenger*'s STS-51-F mission.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This failure had no effect on mission objectives or duration.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] For efficiency reasons, higher temperatures are desirable, but materials lose their strength if the temperature becomes too high.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Rockets run with combustion temperatures that can reach 6,000 °F (3,300 °C; 3,600 K).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Most other jet engines have gas turbines in the hot exhaust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Due to their larger surface area, they are harder to cool and hence there is a need to run the combustion processes at much lower temperatures, losing efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] In addition, duct engines use air as an oxidant, which contains 78% largely unreactive nitrogen, which dilutes the reaction and lowers the temperatures.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Rockets have none of these inherent combustion temperature limiters.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The temperatures reached by combustion in rocket engines often substantially exceed the melting points of the nozzle and combustion chamber materials (about 1,200 K for copper).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Most construction materials will also combust if exposed to high temperature oxidiser, which leads to a number of design challenges.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The nozzle and combustion chamber walls must not be allowed to combust, melt, or vaporize (sometimes facetiously termed an "engine-rich exhaust").
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Rockets that use common construction materials such as aluminium, steel, nickel or copper alloys must employ cooling systems to limit the temperatures that engine structures experience.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Regenerative cooling, where the propellant is passed through tubes around the combustion chamber or nozzle, and other techniques, such as film cooling, are employed to give longer nozzle and chamber life.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] These techniques ensure that a gaseous thermal boundary layer touching the material is kept below the temperature which would cause the material to catastrophically fail.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Material exceptions that can sustain rocket combustion temperatures to a certain degree are carbon–carbon materials and rhenium, although both are subject to oxidation under certain conditions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Other refractory alloys, such as alumina, molybdenum, tantalum or tungsten have been tried, but were given up on due to various issues.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Materials technology, combined with the engine design, is a limiting factor in chemical rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] In rockets, the heat fluxes that can pass through the wall are among the highest in engineering; fluxes are generally in the range of 0.8–80 MW/m2 (0.5–50 BTU/in2-sec).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The strongest heat fluxes are found at the throat, which often sees twice that found in the associated chamber and nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This is due to the combination of high speeds (which gives a very thin boundary layer), and although lower than the chamber, the high temperatures seen there.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] (See § Nozzle above for temperatures in nozzle).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Radiative cooling: The engine is made of one or several refractory materials, which take heat flux until its outer thrust chamber wall glows red- or white-hot, radiating the heat away.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Dump cooling: A cryogenic propellant, usually hydrogen, is passed around the nozzle and dumped.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This cooling method has various issues, such as wasting propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Regenerative cooling: The fuel (and possibly, the oxidiser) of a liquid rocket engine is routed around the nozzle before being injected into the combustion chamber or preburner.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This is the most widely applied method of rocket engine cooling.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Film cooling: The engine is designed with rows of multiple orifices lining the inside wall through which additional propellant is injected, cooling the chamber wall as it evaporates.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This method is often used in cases where the heat fluxes are especially high, likely in combination with regenerative cooling.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] A more efficient subtype of film cooling is transpiration cooling, in which propellant passes through a porous inner combustion chamber wall and transpirates.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] So far, this method has not seen usage due to various issues with this concept.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket engines may also use several cooling methods.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] In all cases, another effect that aids in cooling the rocket engine chamber wall is a thin layer of combustion gases (a boundary layer) that is notably cooler than the combustion temperature.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Disruption of the boundary layer may occur during cooling failures or combustion instabilities, and wall failure typically occurs soon after.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] With regenerative cooling a second boundary layer is found in the coolant channels around the chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This boundary layer thickness needs to be as small as possible, since the boundary layer acts as an insulator between the wall and the coolant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This may be achieved by making the coolant velocity in the channels as high as possible.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Liquid-fuelled engines are often run fuel-rich, which lowers combustion temperatures.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This reduces heat loads on the engine and allows lower cost materials and a simplified cooling system.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This can also *increase* performance by lowering the average molecular weight of the exhaust and increasing the efficiency with which combustion heat is converted to kinetic exhaust energy.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket propellants require a high energy per unit mass (specific energy), which must be balanced against the tendency of highly energetic propellants to spontaneously explode.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Assuming that the chemical potential energy of the propellants can be safely stored, the combustion process results in a great deal of heat being released.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] A significant fraction of this heat is transferred to kinetic energy in the engine nozzle, propelling the rocket forward in combination with the mass of combustion products released.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Ideally all the reaction energy appears as kinetic energy of the exhaust gases, as exhaust velocity is the single most important performance parameter of an engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] However, real exhaust species are molecules, which typically have translation, vibrational, and rotational modes with which to dissipate energy.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Of these, only translation can do useful work to the vehicle, and while energy does transfer between modes this process occurs on a timescale far in excess of the time required for the exhaust to leave the nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The more chemical bonds an exhaust molecule has, the more rotational and vibrational modes it will have.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Consequently, it is generally desirable for the exhaust species to be as simple as possible, with a diatomic molecule composed of light, abundant atoms such as H2 being ideal in practical terms.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] However, in the case of a chemical rocket, hydrogen is a reactant and reducing agent, not a product.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] An oxidizing agent, most typically oxygen or an oxygen-rich species, must be introduced into the combustion process, adding mass and chemical bonds to the exhaust species.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] An additional advantage of light molecules is that they may be accelerated to high velocity at temperatures that can be contained by currently available materials - the high gas temperatures in rocket engines pose serious problems for the engineering of survivable motors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] When computing the specific reaction energy of a given propellant combination, the entire mass of the propellants (both fuel and oxidiser) must be included.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The exception is in the case of air-breathing engines, which use atmospheric oxygen and consequently have to carry less mass for a given energy output.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Fuels for car or turbojet engines have a much better effective energy output per unit mass of propellant that must be carried, but are similar per unit mass of fuel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Computer programs that predict the performance of propellants in rocket engines are available.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] With liquid and hybrid rockets, immediate ignition of the propellants as they first enter the combustion chamber is essential.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Ignition can be achieved by a number of different methods; a pyrotechnic charge can be used, a plasma torch can be used, or electric spark ignition may be employed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Some fuel/oxidiser combinations ignite on contact (hypergolic), and non-hypergolic fuels can be "chemically ignited" by priming the fuel lines with hypergolic propellants (popular in Russian engines).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Gaseous propellants generally will not cause hard starts, with rockets the total injector area is less than the throat thus the chamber pressure tends to ambient prior to ignition and high pressures cannot form even if the entire chamber is full of flammable gas at ignition.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Solid propellants are usually ignited with one-shot pyrotechnic devices and combustion usually proceeds through total consumption of the propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Once ignited, rocket chambers are self-sustaining and igniters are not needed and combustion usually proceeds through total consumption of the propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Indeed, chambers often spontaneously reignite if they are restarted after being shut down for a few seconds.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Unless designed for re-ignition, when cooled, many rockets cannot be restarted without at least minor maintenance, such as replacement of the pyrotechnic igniter or even refueling of the propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket jets vary depending on the rocket engine, design altitude, altitude, thrust and other factors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Carbon-rich exhausts from kerosene-based fuels such as RP-1 are often orange in colour due to the black-body radiation of the unburnt particles, in addition to the blue Swan bands.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Peroxide oxidiser-based rockets and hydrogen rocket jets contain largely steam and are nearly invisible to the naked eye but shine brightly in the ultraviolet and infrared ranges.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Jets from solid-propellant rockets can be highly visible, as the propellant frequently contains metals such as elemental aluminium which burns with an orange-white flame and adds energy to the combustion process.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket engines which burn liquid hydrogen and oxygen will exhibit a nearly transparent exhaust, due to it being mostly superheated steam (water vapour), plus some unburned hydrogen.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The nozzle is usually over-expanded at sea level, and the exhaust can exhibit visible shock diamonds through a schlieren effect caused by the incandescence of the exhaust gas.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The shape of the jet varies for a fixed-area nozzle as the expansion ratio varies with altitude: at high altitude all rockets are grossly under-expanded, and a quite small percentage of exhaust gases actually end up expanding forwards.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The solar thermal rocket would make use of solar power to directly heat reaction mass, and therefore does not require an electrical generator as most other forms of solar-powered propulsion do.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] A solar thermal rocket only has to carry the means of capturing solar energy, such as concentrators and mirrors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The heated propellant is fed through a conventional rocket nozzle to produce thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The engine thrust is directly related to the surface area of the solar collector and to the local intensity of the solar radiation and inversely proportional to the *I*sp.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Nuclear propulsion includes a wide variety of propulsion methods that use some form of nuclear reaction as their primary power source.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] According to the writings of the Roman Aulus Gellius, the earliest known example of jet propulsion was in c.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] 400 BC, when a Greek Pythagorean named Archytas propelled a wooden bird along wires using steam.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] However, it was not powerful enough to take off under its own thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The *aeolipile* described in the first century BC, often known as *Hero's engine*, consisted of a pair of steam rocket nozzles mounted on a bearing.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] It was created almost two millennia before the Industrial Revolution but the principles behind it were not well understood, and it was not developed into a practical power source.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The availability of black powder to propel projectiles was a precursor to the development of the first solid rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Ninth-century Chinese Taoist alchemists discovered black powder in a search for the elixir of life; this accidental discovery led to fire arrows which were the first rocket engines to leave the ground.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] It is stated that "the reactive forces of incendiaries were probably not applied to the propulsion of projectiles prior to the 13th century".
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] A turning point in rocket technology emerged with a short manuscript entitled *Liber Ignium ad Comburendos Hostes* (abbreviated as *The Book of Fires*).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The manuscript is composed of recipes for creating incendiary weapons from the mid-eighth to the end of the thirteenth centuries—two of which are rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The first recipe calls for one part of colophonium and sulfur added to six parts of saltpeter (potassium nitrate) dissolved in laurel oil, then inserted into hollow wood and lit to "fly away suddenly to whatever place you wish and burn up everything".
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The second recipe combines one pound of sulfur, two pounds of charcoal, and six pounds of saltpeter—all finely powdered on a marble slab.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This powder mixture is packed firmly into a long and narrow case.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The introduction of saltpeter into pyrotechnic mixtures connected the shift from hurled Greek fire into self-propelled rocketry.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Articles and books on the subject of rocketry appeared increasingly from the fifteenth through seventeenth centuries.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] In the sixteenth century, German military engineer Conrad Haas (1509–1576) wrote a manuscript which introduced the construction of multi-staged rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket engines were also put in use by Tippu Sultan, the king of Mysore.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] These usually consisted of a tube of soft hammered iron about 8 in (20 cm) long and 1+1⁄2–3 in (3.8–7.6 cm) diameter, closed at one end, packed with black powder propellant and strapped to a shaft of bamboo about 4 ft (120 cm) long.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] A rocket carrying about one pound of powder could travel almost 1,000 yards (910 m).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] These 'rockets', fitted with swords, would travel several meters in the air before coming down with sword edges facing the enemy.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] These were used very effectively against the British empire.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Slow development of this technology continued up to the later 19th century, when Russian Konstantin Tsiolkovsky first wrote about liquid-fuelled rocket engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] He was the first to develop the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation, though it was not published widely for some years.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The modern solid- and liquid-fuelled engines became realities early in the 20th century, thanks to the American physicist Robert Goddard.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Goddard was the first to use a De Laval nozzle on a solid-propellant (gunpowder) rocket engine, doubling the thrust and increasing the efficiency by a factor of about twenty-five.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] This was the birth of the modern rocket engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] He calculated from his independently derived rocket equation that a reasonably sized rocket, using solid fuel, could place a one-pound payload on the Moon.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Goddard began to use liquid propellants in 1921, and in 1926 became the first to launch a liquid-fuelled rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Goddard pioneered the use of the De Laval nozzle, lightweight propellant tanks, small light turbopumps, thrust vectoring, the smoothly-throttled liquid fuel engine, regenerative cooling, and curtain cooling.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] During the late 1930s, German scientists, such as Wernher von Braun and Hellmuth Walter, investigated installing liquid-fuelled rockets in military aircraft (Heinkel He 112, He 111, He 176 and Messerschmitt Me 163).
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The turbopump was employed by German scientists in World War II.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Until then cooling the nozzle had been problematic, and the A4 ballistic missile used dilute alcohol for the fuel, which reduced the combustion temperature sufficiently.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Staged combustion (*Замкнутая схема*) was first proposed by Alexey Isaev in 1949.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The first staged combustion engine was the S1.5400 used in the Soviet planetary rocket, designed by Melnikov, a former assistant to Isaev.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] About the same time (1959), Nikolai Kuznetsov began work on the closed cycle engine NK-9 for Korolev's orbital ICBM, GR-1.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Kuznetsov later evolved that design into the NK-15 and NK-33 engines for the unsuccessful Lunar N1 rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] In the West, the first laboratory staged-combustion test engine was built in Germany in 1963, by Ludwig Boelkow.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Liquid hydrogen engines were first successfully developed in America: the RL-10 engine first flew in 1962.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] Its successor, the Rocketdyne J-2, was used in the Apollo program's Saturn V rocket to send humans to the Moon.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The high specific impulse and low density of liquid hydrogen lowered the upper stage mass and the overall size and cost of the vehicle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/rocket-engine-p02] The record for most engines on one rocket flight is 44, set by NASA in 2016 on a Black Brant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] A **solid-propellant rocket** or **solid rocket** is a rocket with a rocket engine that uses solid propellants (fuel/oxidizer).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The earliest rockets were solid-fuel rockets powered by gunpowder.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The inception of gunpowder rockets in warfare can be credited to the medieval Chinese, and in the 13th century, the Mongols played a pivotal role in facilitating their westward adoption.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] All rockets used some form of solid or powdered propellant until the 20th century, when liquid-propellant rockets offered more efficient and controllable alternatives.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Because of their simplicity and reliability, solid rockets are still used today in military armaments worldwide, model rockets, solid rocket boosters and on larger applications.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Since solid-fuel rockets can remain in storage for an extended period without much propellant degradation, and since they almost always launch reliably, they have been frequently used in military applications such as missiles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The lower performance of solid propellants (as compared to liquids) does not favor their use as primary propulsion in modern medium-to-large launch vehicles customarily used for commercial satellites and major space probes.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Solids are, however, frequently used as strap-on boosters to increase payload capacity or as spin-stabilized add-on upper stages when higher-than-normal velocities are required.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid rockets are used as light launch vehicles for low Earth orbit (LEO) payloads under 2 tons or escape payloads up to 500 kilograms (1,100 lb).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] A simple solid rocket motor consists of a casing, nozzle, grain (propellant charge), and igniter.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The solid grain mass burns in a predictable fashion to produce exhaust gases, the flow of which is described by Taylor–Culick flow.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The nozzle dimensions are calculated to maintain a design chamber pressure, while producing thrust from the exhaust gases.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Once ignited, a simple solid rocket motor cannot be shut off, as it contains all the ingredients necessary for combustion within the chamber in which they are burned.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] More advanced solid rocket motors can be throttled, or extinguished and re-ignited, by control of the nozzle geometry or through the use of vent ports.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Further, pulsed rocket motors that burn in segments, and that can be ignited upon command are available.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Modern designs may also include a steerable nozzle for guidance, avionics, recovery hardware (parachutes), self-destruct mechanisms, APUs, controllable tactical motors, controllable divert and attitude control motors, and thermal management materials.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The medieval Song dynasty Chinese invented the solid-propellant rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Each arrow took the form of a simple, solid-propellant rocket tube that was filled with gunpowder.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] One open end allowed the gas to escape and was attached to a long stick that acted as a guidance system for flight direction control.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The first rockets with tubes of cast iron were used by the Kingdom of Mysore under Hyder Ali and Tipu Sultan in the 1750s.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] These rockets had a reach of targets up to a mile and a half away.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] These were extremely effective in the Second Anglo-Mysore War that ended in a humiliating defeat for the British East India Company.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Word of the success of the Mysore rockets against the British triggered research in England, France, Ireland and elsewhere.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] When the British finally conquered the fort of Srirangapatana in 1799, hundreds of rockets were shipped off to the Royal Arsenal near London to be reverse-engineered.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] This led to the first industrial manufacture of military rockets with the Congreve rocket in 1804.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In 1921 the Soviet research and development laboratory Gas Dynamics Laboratory began developing solid-propellant rockets, which resulted in the first launch in 1928, that flew for approximately 1,300 metres.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] These rockets were used in 1931 for the world's first successful use of rockets to assist take-off of aircraft.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The research continued from 1933 by the Reactive Scientific Research Institute (RNII) with the development of the RS-82 and RS-132 rockets, including designing several variations for ground-to-air, ground-to-ground, air-to-ground and air-to-air combat.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The earliest known use by the Soviet Air Force of aircraft-launched unguided anti-aircraft rockets in combat against heavier-than-air aircraft took place in August 1939, during the Battle of Khalkhin Gol.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In June 1938, the RNII began developing a multiple rocket launcher based on the RS-132 rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In August 1939, the completed product was the BM-13 / Katyusha rocket launcher.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Towards the end of 1938 the first significant large scale testing of the rocket launchers took place, 233 rockets of various types were used.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] A salvo of rockets could completely straddle a target at a range of 5,500 metres (3.4 mi).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] By the end of World War II total production of rocket launchers reached about 10,000. with 12 million rockets of the RS type produced for the Soviet armed forces.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In the United States modern castable composite solid rocket motors were invented by the American aerospace engineer Jack Parsons at Caltech in 1942 when he replaced double base propellant with roofing asphalt and potassium perchlorate.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] This made possible slow-burning rocket motors of adequate size and with sufficient shelf-life for jet-assisted take off applications.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Charles Bartley, employed at JPL (Caltech), substituted curable synthetic rubber for the gooey asphalt, creating a flexible but geometrically stable load-bearing propellant grain that bonded securely to the motor casing.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] This made possible much larger solid rocket motors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Atlantic Research Corporation significantly boosted composite propellant Isp in 1954 by increasing the amount of powdered aluminium in the propellant to as much as 20%.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid-propellant rocket technology got its largest boost in technical innovation, size and capability with the various mid-20th century government initiatives to develop increasingly capable military missiles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Many other governments also developed these military technologies over the next 50 years.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Some designs have had solid rocket upper stages as well.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Examples flying in the 2010s include the European Ariane 5, US Atlas V and Space Shuttle, and Japan's H-II.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The largest solid rocket motors ever built were Aerojet's three 6.60-meter (260 in) monolithic solid motors cast in Florida.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The nozzle throat was large enough to walk through standing up.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The motor was capable of serving as a 1-to-1 replacement for the 8-engine Saturn I liquid-propellant first stage but was never used as such.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Motor 260 SL-3 was of similar length and weight but had a maximum thrust of 24 MN (5,400,000 lbf) and a shorter duration.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Design begins with the total impulse required, which determines the fuel and oxidizer mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Grain geometry and chemistry are then chosen to satisfy the required motor characteristics.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The following are chosen or solved simultaneously.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The grain may or may not be bonded to the casing.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Case-bonded motors are more difficult to design, since the deformation of the case and the grain under flight must be compatible.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Common modes of failure in solid rocket motors include fracture of the grain, failure of case bonding, and air pockets in the grain.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] All of these produce an instantaneous increase in burn surface area and a corresponding increase in exhaust gas production rate and pressure, which may rupture the casing.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Another failure mode is casing seal failure.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Seals are required in casings that have to be opened to load the grain.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Once a seal fails, hot gas will erode the escape path and result in failure.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] This was the cause of the Space Shuttle *Challenger* disaster.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid rocket fuel deflagrates from the surface of exposed propellant in the combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In this fashion, the geometry of the propellant inside the rocket motor plays an important role in the overall motor performance.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] As the surface of the propellant burns, the shape evolves (a subject of study in internal ballistics), most often changing the propellant surface area exposed to the combustion gases.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The casing may be constructed from a range of materials.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Cardboard is used for small black powder model motors, whereas aluminium is used for larger composite-fuel hobby motors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Steel was used for the space shuttle boosters.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Filament-wound graphite epoxy casings are used for high-performance motors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The casing must be designed to withstand the pressure and resulting stresses of the rocket motor, possibly at elevated temperature.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] For design, the casing is considered a pressure vessel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] To protect the casing from corrosive hot gases, a sacrificial thermal liner on the inside of the casing is often implemented, which ablates to prolong the life of the motor casing.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] A convergent-divergent design accelerates the exhaust gas out of the nozzle to produce thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The nozzle must be constructed from a material that can withstand the heat of the combustion gas flow.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Often, heat-resistant carbon-based materials are used, such as amorphous graphite or reinforced carbon–carbon.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Some designs include directional control of the exhaust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] This can be accomplished by gimballing the nozzle, as in the Space Shuttle SRBs, by the use of jet vanes in the exhaust as in the V-2 rocket, or by liquid injection thrust vectoring (LITV).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] LITV consists of injecting a liquid into the exhaust stream after the nozzle throat.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The liquid then vaporizes, and in most cases chemically reacts, adding mass flow to one side of the exhaust stream and thus providing a control moment.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] For example, the Titan IIIC solid boosters injected dinitrogen tetroxide for LITV; the tanks can be seen on the sides of the rocket between the main center stage and the boosters.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] An early Minuteman first stage used a single motor with four gimballed nozzles to provide pitch, yaw, and roll control.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] A typical, well-designed ammonium perchlorate composite propellant (APCP) first-stage motor may have a vacuum specific impulse (*I*sp) as high as 285.6 seconds (2.801 km/s) (Titan IVB SRMU).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Propellant fractions are usually somewhat higher for (non-segmented) solid propellant first stages than for upper stages.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Castor 120 and Castor 30 are 2.36 and 2.34 meters (93 and 92 in) in diameter, respectively, and serve as stages on the Athena IC and IIC commercial launch vehicles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] A four-stage Athena II using Castor 120s as both first and second stages became the first commercially developed launch vehicle to launch a lunar probe (*Lunar Prospector*) in 1998.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid rockets can provide high thrust for relatively low cost.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] For this reason, solids have been used as initial stages in rockets (for example the Space Shuttle), while reserving high specific impulse engines, especially less massive hydrogen-fueled engines, for higher stages.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In addition, solid rockets have a long history as the final boost stage for satellites due to their simplicity, reliability, compactness and reasonably high mass fraction.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] A spin-stabilized solid rocket motor is sometimes added when extra velocity is required, such as for a mission to a comet or the outer solar system, because a spinner does not require a guidance system (on the newly added stage).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Thiokol's extensive family of mostly titanium-cased *Star* space motors has been widely used, especially on Delta launch vehicles and as spin-stabilized upper stages to launch satellites from the cargo bay of the Space Shuttle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] *Star* motors have propellant fractions as high as 94.6% but add-on structures and equipment reduce the operating mass fraction by 2% or more.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Higher performing solid rocket propellants are used in large strategic missiles (as opposed to commercial launch vehicles).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] HMX, C4H8N4(NO2)4, a nitramine with greater energy than ammonium perchlorate, was used in the propellant of the Peacekeeper ICBM and is the main ingredient in NEPE-75 propellant used in the Trident II D-5 Fleet Ballistic Missile.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] It is because of explosive hazard that the higher energy military solid propellants containing HMX are not used in commercial launch vehicles except when the LV is an adapted ballistic missile already containing HMX propellant (Minotaur IV and V based on the retired Peacekeeper ICBMs).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The Naval Air Weapons Station at China Lake, California, developed a new compound, C6H6N6(NO2)6, called simply CL-20 (China Lake compound #20).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Compared to HMX, CL-20 has 14% more energy per mass, 20% more energy per volume, and a higher oxygen-to-fuel ratio.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] One of the motivations for development of these very high energy density military solid propellants is to achieve mid-course exo-atmospheric ABM capability from missiles small enough to fit in existing ship-based below-deck vertical launch tubes and air-mobile truck-mounted launch tubes.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] CL-20 propellant compliant with Congress' 2004 insensitive munitions (IM) law has been demonstrated and may, as its cost comes down, be suitable for use in commercial launch vehicles, with a very significant increase in performance compared with the currently favored APCP solid propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] An attractive attribute for military use is the ability for solid rocket propellant to remain loaded in the rocket for long durations and then be reliably launched at a moment's notice.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Black powder (gunpowder) is composed of charcoal (fuel), potassium nitrate (oxidizer), and sulfur (fuel and catalyst).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] It is one of the oldest pyrotechnic compositions with application to rocketry.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In modern times, black powder finds use in low-power model rockets (such as Estes and Quest rockets), as it is cheap and fairly easy to produce.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The fuel grain is typically a mixture of pressed fine powder (into a solid, hard slug), with a burn rate that is highly dependent upon exact composition and operating conditions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The specific impulse of black powder is low, around 80 s (0.78 km/s).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The grain is sensitive to fracture and, therefore, catastrophic failure.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Black powder does not typically find use in motors above 40 newtons (9.0 pounds-force) thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] ZS is most often employed as a novelty propellant as the rocket accelerates extremely quickly leaving a spectacular large orange fireball behind it.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] DB propellants are composed of two monopropellant fuel components where one typically acts as a high-energy (yet unstable) monopropellant and the other acts as a lower-energy stabilizing (and gelling) monopropellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In typical circumstances, nitroglycerin is dissolved in a nitrocellulose gel and solidified with additives.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] DB propellants are implemented in applications where minimal smoke is required yet a medium-high Isp of roughly 235 s (2.30 km/s) is required.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The addition of metal fuels (such as aluminium) can increase performance to around 250 s (2.5 km/s), though metal oxide nucleation in the exhaust can turn the smoke opaque.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] A powdered oxidizer and powdered metal fuel are intimately mixed and immobilized with a rubbery binder (that also acts as a fuel).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Composite propellants are often either ammonium-nitrate-based (ANCP) or ammonium-perchlorate-based (APCP).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Aluminium is used as fuel because it has a reasonable specific energy density, a high volumetric energy density, and is difficult to ignite accidentally.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Composite propellants are cast, and retain their shape after the rubber binder, such as Hydroxyl-terminated polybutadiene (HTPB), cross-links (solidifies) with the aid of a curative additive.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Because of its high performance, moderate ease of manufacturing, and moderate cost, APCP finds widespread use in space, military, and amateur rockets, whereas cheaper and less efficient ANCP finds use in amateur rocketry and gas generators.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Ammonium dinitramide, NH4N(NO2)2, is being considered as a 1-to-1 chlorine-free substitute for ammonium perchlorate in composite propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Unlike ammonium nitrate, ADN can be substituted for AP without a loss in motor performance.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Polyurethane-bound aluminium-APCP solid fuel was used in the submarine-launched Polaris missiles.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] It developed a specific impulse of 242 seconds (2.37 km/s) at sea level or 268 seconds (2.63 km/s) in a vacuum.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The 2005–2009 Constellation Program was to use a similar PBAN-bound APCP.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In 2009, a group succeeded in creating a propellant of water and nanoaluminium (ALICE).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In general, rocket candy propellants are an oxidizer (typically potassium nitrate) and a sugar fuel (typically dextrose, sorbitol, or sucrose) that are cast into shape by gently melting the propellant constituents together and pouring or packing the amorphous colloid into a mold.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Candy propellants generate a low-medium specific impulse of roughly 130 s (1.3 km/s) and, thus, are used primarily by amateur and experimental rocketeers.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Typical HEC propellants start with a standard composite propellant mixture (such as APCP) and add a high-energy explosive to the mix.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] This extra component usually is in the form of small crystals of RDX or HMX, both of which have higher energy than ammonium perchlorate.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Despite a modest increase in specific impulse, implementation is limited due to the increased hazards of the high-explosive additives.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Composite modified double base propellants start with a nitrocellulose/nitroglycerin double base propellant as a binder and add solids (typically ammonium perchlorate (AP) and powdered aluminium) normally used in composite propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The ammonium perchlorate makes up the oxygen deficit introduced by using nitrocellulose, improving the overall specific impulse.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The aluminium improves specific impulse as well as combustion stability.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] High performing propellants such as NEPE-75 used to fuel the Trident II D-5 SLBM replace most of the AP with polyethylene glycol-bound HMX, further increasing specific impulse.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The mixing of composite and double base propellant ingredients has become so common as to blur the functional definition of double base propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] One of the most active areas of solid propellant research is the development of high-energy, minimum-signature propellant using C6H6N6(NO2)6 CL-20 (China Lake compound #20), which has 14% higher energy per mass and 20% higher energy density than HMX.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The new propellant has been successfully developed and tested in tactical rocket motors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The propellant is non-polluting: acid-free, solid particulates-free, and lead-free.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] It is also smokeless and has only a faint shock diamond pattern that is visible in the otherwise transparent exhaust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Without the bright flame and dense smoke trail produced by the burning of aluminized propellants, these smokeless propellants all but eliminate the risk of giving away the positions from which the missiles are fired.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The new CL-20 propellant is shock-insensitive (hazard class 1.3) as opposed to current HMX smokeless propellants which are highly detonable (hazard class 1.1).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] CL-20 is considered a major breakthrough in solid rocket propellant technology but has yet to see widespread use because costs remain high.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Electric solid propellants (ESPs) are a family of high performance plastisol solid propellants that can be ignited and throttled by the application of electric current.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Unlike conventional rocket motor propellants that are difficult to control and extinguish, ESPs can be ignited reliably at precise intervals and durations.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] It requires no moving parts and the propellant is insensitive to flames or electrical sparks.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid propellant rocket motors can be bought for use in model rocketry; they are normally small cylinders of black powder fuel with an integral nozzle and optionally a small charge that is set off when the propellant is exhausted after a time delay.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] This charge can be used to trigger a camera, or deploy a parachute.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Without this charge and delay, the motor may ignite a second stage (black powder only).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In amateur rocketry, "candy" propellants are common because they offer relative safety and ease of production, ingredients that are readily available publicly, and a higher specific impulse than blackpowder motors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] In mid- and high-power rocketry, commercially made APCP motors are widely used.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] They can be designed as either single-use or reloadables.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] These motors are available in impulse ranges from "A" (1.26 Ns– 2.50 Ns) to "O" (20.48 kNs – 40.96 kNs), from several manufacturers.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] They are manufactured in standardized diameters and varying lengths depending on required impulse.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Different propellant formulations are available to produce different thrust profiles, as well as special effects such as colored flames, smoke trails, or large quantities of sparks (produced by adding titanium sponge to the mix).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Almost all sounding rockets use solid motors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Due to reliability, ease of storage and handling, solid rockets are used on missiles and ICBMs.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid rockets are suitable for launching small payloads to orbital velocities, especially if three or more stages are used.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Many of these are based on repurposed ICBMs.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Gravity-1 is the largest-payload-capacity rocket to get into orbit with only solid rocket motors.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Larger liquid-fueled orbital rockets often use solid rocket boosters to gain enough initial thrust to launch the fully fueled rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid fuel is also used for some upper stages, particularly the Star 37 (sometimes referred to as the "Burner" upper stage) and the Star 48 (sometimes referred to as the "Payload Assist Module", or PAM), both manufactured originally by Thiokol, and today by Northrop Grumman.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] They are used to lift large payloads to intended orbits (such as the Global Positioning System satellites), or smaller payloads to interplanetary—or even interstellar—trajectories.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Another solid-fuel upper stage, used by the Space Shuttle and the Titan IV, was the Boeing-manufactured Inertial Upper Stage (IUS).
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] Some rockets, like the Antares (manufactured by Northrop Grumman), have mandatory solid-fuel upper stages.
[src:rocket-propulsion/solid-propellant-rocket] The Antares rocket uses the Northrop Grumman-manufactured Castor 30 as an upper stage.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Several methods of pragmatic spacecraft propulsion have been developed, each having its own drawbacks and advantages.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Most satellites have simple reliable chemical thrusters (often monopropellant rockets) or resistojet rockets for orbital station-keeping, while a few use momentum wheels for attitude control.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Russian and antecedent Soviet bloc satellites have used electric propulsion for decades, and newer Western geo-orbiting spacecraft are starting to use them for north–south station-keeping and orbit raising.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Interplanetary vehicles mostly use chemical rockets as well, although a few have used electric propulsion such as ion thrusters and Hall-effect thrusters.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Various technologies need to support everything from small satellites and robotic deep space exploration to space stations and human missions to Mars.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Hypothetical in-space propulsion technologies describe propulsion technologies that could meet future space science and exploration needs.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] These propulsion technologies are intended to provide effective exploration of the Solar System and may permit mission designers to plan missions to "fly anytime, anywhere, and complete a host of science objectives at the destinations" and with greater reliability and safety.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] A spacecraft propulsion system provides propulsive force for orbital transfer, interplanetary trajectories, and potentially for landing and ascent.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] In addition, propulsion is needed for orienting and positioning the spacecraft in route as well as orbit maintenance (reaction control, station keeping, precision pointing, and orbital maneuvering).
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Earth's surface is situated fairly deep in a gravity well; the escape velocity required to leave its orbit is 11.2 kilometers per second.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Thus for destinations beyond, propulsion systems need enough propellant and to be of high enough efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The same is true for other planets and moons, albeit some have lower gravity wells.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] As human beings evolved in a gravitational field of "one *g*" (9.81 m/s2), it would be most comfortable for a human spaceflight propulsion system to provide that acceleration continuously (though human bodies can tolerate much larger accelerations over short periods).
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The occupants of a rocket or spaceship having such a propulsion system would be free from the ill effects of free fall, such as nausea, muscular weakness, reduced sense of taste, or leaching of calcium from their bones.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Almost all types of spacecraft propulsion are reaction engines, which produce thrust by expelling reaction mass, in accordance with Newton's third law of motion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The Tsiolkovsky rocket equation shows, using the law of conservation of momentum, that for a rocket engine propulsion method to change the momentum of a spacecraft, it must change the momentum of something else in the opposite direction.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] In other words, the rocket must exhaust mass opposite the spacecraft's acceleration direction, with such exhausted mass called propellant or reaction mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] For this to happen, both reaction mass and energy are needed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The impulse provided by launching a particle of reaction mass with mass m at velocity v is *mv*.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] But (following Newton's second law of motion) this particle has kinetic energy ⁠1/2⁠*mv*2, which must come from somewhere.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] In a conventional solid, liquid, or hybrid rocket, fuel is burned, providing the energy, and the reaction products are allowed to flow out of the engine nozzle, providing the reaction mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] In an ion thruster, electricity is used to accelerate ions behind the spacecraft.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Here other sources must provide the electrical energy (e.g. a solar panel or a nuclear reactor), whereas the ions provide the reaction mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The rate of change of velocity is called acceleration and the rate of change of momentum is called force.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] To reach a given velocity, one can apply a small acceleration over a long period of time, or a large acceleration over a short time; similarly, one can achieve a given impulse with a large force over a short time or a small force over a long time.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] This means that for maneuvering in space, a propulsion method that produces tiny accelerations for a long time can often produce the same impulse as another which produces large accelerations for a short time.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] However, when launching from a planet, tiny accelerations cannot overcome the planet's gravitational pull and so cannot be used.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Some designs however, operate without internal reaction mass by taking advantage of magnetic fields or light pressure to change the spacecraft's momentum.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] When discussing the efficiency of a propulsion system, designers often focus on the effective use of the reaction mass, which must be carried along with the rocket and is irretrievably consumed when used.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Spacecraft performance can be quantified in *amount of change in momentum per unit of propellant consumed,* also called specific impulse.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] This is a measure of the amount of impulse that can be obtained from a fixed amount of reaction mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The higher the specific impulse, the better the efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Ion propulsion engines have high specific impulse (~3000 s) and low thrust whereas chemical rockets like monopropellant or bipropellant rocket engines have a low specific impulse (~300 s) but high thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The impulse per unit weight-on-Earth (typically designated by $I_{\text{sp}}$ ) has units of seconds.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Because the weight on Earth of the reaction mass is often unimportant when discussing vehicles in space, specific impulse can also be discussed in terms of impulse per unit mass, with the same units as velocity (e.g., meters per second).
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] This measure is equivalent to the effective exhaust velocity of the engine, and is typically designated $v_{e}$ .
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Either the change in momentum per unit of propellant used by a spacecraft, or the velocity of the propellant exiting the spacecraft, can be used to measure its specific impulse.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The two values differ by a factor of the standard acceleration due to gravity, *g*n, 9.80665 m/s² ( $I_{\text{sp}}g_{\mathrm {n} }=v_{e}$ ).
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] In contrast to chemical rockets, electrodynamic rockets use electric or magnetic fields to accelerate a charged propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The benefit of this method is that it can achieve exhaust velocities, and therefore $I_{\text{sp}}$ , more than 10 times greater than those of a chemical engine, producing steady thrust with far less fuel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] With a conventional chemical propulsion system, 2% of a rocket's total mass might make it to the destination, with the other 98% having been consumed as fuel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] With an electric propulsion system, 70% of what is aboard in low Earth orbit can make it to a deep-space destination.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Chemical rockets transform propellants into most of the energy needed to propel them, but their electromagnetic equivalents must carry or produce the power required to create and accelerate propellants.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Because there are currently practical limits on the amount of power available on a spacecraft, these engines are not suitable for launch vehicles or when a spacecraft needs a quick, large impulse, such as when it brakes to enter a capture orbit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Even so, because electrodynamic rockets offer very high $I_{\text{sp}}$ , mission planners are increasingly willing to sacrifice power and thrust (and the extra time it will take to get a spacecraft where it needs to go) in order to save large amounts of propellant mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Spacecraft operate in many areas of space.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] These include orbital maneuvering, interplanetary travel, and interstellar travel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Artificial satellites are first launched into the desired altitude by conventional liquid/solid propelled rockets, after which the satellite may use onboard propulsion systems for orbital stationkeeping.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Once in the desired orbit, they often need some form of attitude control so that they are correctly pointed with respect to the Earth, the Sun, and possibly some astronomical object of interest.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] They are also subject to drag from the thin atmosphere, so that to stay in orbit for a long period of time some form of propulsion is occasionally necessary to make small corrections (orbital station-keeping).
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Many satellites need to be moved from one orbit to another from time to time, and this also requires propulsion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] A satellite's useful life is usually over once it has exhausted its ability to adjust its orbit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] For interplanetary travel, a spacecraft can use its engines to leave Earth's orbit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] It is not explicitly necessary as the initial boost given by the rocket, gravity slingshot, monopropellant/bipropellent attitude control propulsion system are enough for the exploration of the solar system (see New Horizons).
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Once it has done so, it must make its way to its destination.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Current interplanetary spacecraft do this with a series of short-term trajectory adjustments.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] In between these adjustments, the spacecraft typically moves along its trajectory without accelerating.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The most fuel-efficient means to move from one circular orbit to another is with a Hohmann transfer orbit: the spacecraft begins in a roughly circular orbit around the Sun.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] A short period of thrust in the direction of motion accelerates or decelerates the spacecraft into an elliptical orbit around the Sun which is tangential to its previous orbit and also to the orbit of its destination.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The spacecraft falls freely along this elliptical orbit until it reaches its destination, where another short period of thrust accelerates or decelerates it to match the orbit of its destination.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Special methods such as aerobraking or aerocapture are sometimes used for this final orbital adjustment.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The concept has been successfully tested by the Japanese IKAROS solar sail spacecraft.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Because interstellar distances are great, a tremendous velocity is needed to get a spacecraft to its destination in a reasonable amount of time.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Acquiring such a velocity on launch and getting rid of it on arrival remains a formidable challenge for spacecraft designers.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] No spacecraft capable of short duration (compared to human lifetime) interstellar travel has yet been built, but many hypothetical designs have been discussed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The four conventional and widely used types of spacecraft propulsion are cold gas, monopropellant, bipropellant, and solid motor systems.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Spacecraft propulsion technology can be of several types, such as chemical, electric or nuclear.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] They are distinguished based on the physics of the propulsion system and how thrust is generated.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Other experimental and more theoretical types are also included, depending on their technical maturity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Additionally, there may be credible meritorious in-space propulsion concepts not foreseen or reviewed at the time of publication, and which may be shown to be beneficial to future mission applications.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] A large fraction of rocket engines in use today are chemical rockets; that is, they obtain the energy needed to generate thrust by chemical reactions to create a hot gas that is expanded to produce thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Many different propellant combinations are used to obtain these chemical reactions, including, for example, hydrazine, liquid oxygen, liquid hydrogen, nitrous oxide, and hydrogen peroxide.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] They can be used as a monopropellant or in bi-propellant configurations.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Rocket engines provide essentially the highest specific powers and high specific thrusts of any engine used for spacecraft propulsion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Most rocket engines are internal combustion heat engines (although non-combusting forms exist).
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Rocket engines generally produce a high-temperature reaction mass, as a hot gas, which is achieved by combusting a solid, liquid or gaseous fuel with an oxidiser within a combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The extremely hot gas is then allowed to escape through a high-expansion ratio bell-shaped nozzle, a feature that gives a rocket engine its characteristic shape.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The effect of the nozzle is to accelerate the mass, converting most of the thermal energy into kinetic energy, where exhaust speeds reaching as high as 10 times the speed of sound at sea level are common.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The dominant form of chemical propulsion for satellites has historically been hydrazine, but this fuel is highly toxic and at risk of being banned across Europe.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Non-toxic 'green' alternatives are now being developed to replace hydrazine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Nitrous oxide-based alternatives are garnering traction and government support, with development being led by commercial companies Dawn Aerospace, Impulse Space, and Launcher.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The first nitrous oxide-based system flown in space was by D-Orbit onboard their ION Satellite Carrier (space tug) in 2021, using six Dawn Aerospace B20 thrusters, launched upon a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Rather than relying on high temperature and fluid dynamics to accelerate the reaction mass to high speeds, there are a variety of methods that use electrostatic or electromagnetic forces to accelerate the reaction mass directly, where the reaction mass is usually a stream of ions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Ion propulsion rockets typically heat a plasma or charged gas inside a magnetic bottle and release it via a magnetic nozzle so that no solid matter needs to come in contact with the plasma.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Such an engine uses electric power, first to ionize atoms, and then to create a voltage gradient to accelerate the ions to high exhaust velocities.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] For these drives, at the highest exhaust speeds, energetic efficiency and thrust are all inversely proportional to exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Their very high exhaust velocity means they require huge amounts of energy and thus with practical power sources provide low thrust, but use hardly any fuel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Electric propulsion is commonly used for station keeping on commercial communications satellites and for prime propulsion on some scientific space missions because of their high specific impulse.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] However, they generally have very small values of thrust and therefore must be operated for long durations to provide the total impulse required by a mission.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The idea of electric propulsion dates to 1906, when Robert Goddard considered the possibility in his personal notebook.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Konstantin Tsiolkovsky published the idea in 1911.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Electrical propulsion can be powered by solar energy or nuclear power.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Solar system use solar cells to generate electricity directly; nuclear systems create heat which is converted to electricity, either statically (at efficiency <10%) or dynamically (20-30%).
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Dynamics system need to be large to be practical.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Electric rockets drawing their power from a nuclear source are called nuclear electric rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Chemical power generators are not used due to the far lower total available energy.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] With any current source of electrical power, chemical, nuclear or solar, the maximum amount of power that can be generated limits the amount of thrust that can be produced to a small value.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Power generation adds significant mass to the spacecraft, and ultimately the weight of the power source limits the performance of the vehicle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Nuclear fuels typically have very high specific energy, much higher than chemical fuels, which means that they can generate large amounts of energy per unit mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] This makes them valuable in spaceflight, as it can enable high specific impulses, sometimes even at high thrusts.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The machinery to do this is complex, but research has developed methods for their use in propulsion systems, and some have been tested in a laboratory.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Here, nuclear propulsion moreso refers to the source of propulsion being nuclear, instead of a nuclear electric rocket where a nuclear reactor would provide power (instead of solar panels) for other types of electrical propulsion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Propellantless spacecraft propulsion is any spacecraft propulsion system that accelerates the craft by interacting with the environment rather than expelling on-board propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Systems that have been demonstrated include gravity assist for satellite trajectories in a gravitational field, aerobraking using atmospheric drag, solar sails using radiation pressure from the Sun, and electrodynamic tethers leveraging a planet's magnetic field with a long wire.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Other propellantless systems are only exploratory concepts.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The concept of a gravity assist is a form of propulsion to carry a space probe onward to other destinations without the expense of reaction mass; harnessing the gravitational energy of other celestial objects allows the spacecraft to gain kinetic energy.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] However, more energy can be obtained from the gravity assist if rockets are used via the Oberth effect.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The concept of solar sails rely on radiation pressure from electromagnetic energy, but they require a large collection surface to function effectively.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Japan launched a solar sail-powered spacecraft, IKAROS in May 2010, which successfully demonstrated propulsion and guidance until the mission ended in 2025.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] As further proof of the solar sail concept, NanoSail-D became the first such powered satellite to orbit Earth.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] As of August 2017, NASA confirmed the Sunjammer solar sail project was concluded in 2014 with lessons learned for future space sail projects.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Cubesail programme will be the first mission to demonstrate solar sailing in low Earth orbit, and the first mission to demonstrate full three-axis attitude control of a solar sail.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] A tether propulsion system employs a long cable with a high tensile strength to change a spacecraft's orbit, such as by interaction with a planet's magnetic field or through momentum exchange with another object.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Magnetic sails deflect charged particles from the solar wind with a magnetic field, thereby imparting momentum to the spacecraft.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] For instance, the so-called Magsail is a large superconducting loop proposed for acceleration/deceleration in the solar wind and deceleration in the Interstellar medium.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] A variant is the mini-magnetospheric plasma propulsion system and its successor, the magnetoplasma sail, which inject plasma at a low rate to enhance the magnetic field to more effectively deflect charged particles in a plasma wind.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Beam-powered propulsion is another method of propulsion without reaction mass, and includes sails pushed by laser, microwave, or particle beams.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Beamed power to the spacecraft is considered to have potential, according to NASA and the University of Colorado Boulder.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Advanced, and in some cases theoretical, propulsion technologies may use chemical or nonchemical physics to produce thrust but are generally considered to be of lower technical maturity with challenges that have not been overcome.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] For both human and robotic exploration, traversing the solar system is a struggle against time and distance.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The most distant planets are 4.5–6 billion kilometers from the Sun and to reach them in any reasonable time requires much more capable propulsion systems than conventional chemical rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Rapid inner solar system missions with flexible launch dates are difficult, requiring propulsion systems that are beyond today's current state of the art.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The logistics, and therefore the total system mass required to support sustained human exploration beyond Earth to destinations such as the Moon, Mars, or near-Earth objects, are daunting unless more efficient in-space propulsion technologies are developed and fielded.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] A variety of hypothetical propulsion techniques have been considered that require a deeper understanding of the properties of space, particularly inertial frames and the vacuum state.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] A NASA assessment of its Breakthrough Propulsion Physics Program divides such proposals into those that are non-viable for propulsion purposes, those that are of uncertain potential, and those that are not impossible according to current theories.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Below is a summary of some of the more popular, proven technologies, followed by increasingly speculative methods.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The first is the effective exhaust velocity: the equivalent speed which the propellant leaves the vehicle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] This is not necessarily the most important characteristic of the propulsion method; thrust and power consumption and other factors can be.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The fourth is the maximum delta-v the technique can give without staging.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] For rocket-like propulsion systems, this is a function of mass fraction and exhaust velocity; mass fraction for rocket-like systems is usually limited by propulsion system weight and tankage weight.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] For a system to achieve this limit, the payload may need to be a negligible percentage of the vehicle, and so the practical limit on some systems can be much lower.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] There have been many ideas proposed for launch-assist mechanisms that have the potential of substantially reducing the cost of getting to orbit.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Studies generally show that conventional air-breathing engines, such as ramjets or turbojets are basically too heavy (have too low a thrust/weight ratio) to give significant performance improvement when installed on a launch vehicle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] However, launch vehicles can be air launched from separate lift vehicles (e.g.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] B-29, Pegasus Rocket and White Knight) which do use such propulsion systems.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Jet engines mounted on a launch rail could also be so used.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Normal rocket launch vehicles fly almost vertically before rolling over at an altitude of some tens of kilometers before burning sideways for orbit; this initial vertical climb wastes propellant but is optimal as it greatly reduces airdrag.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Airbreathing engines burn propellant much more efficiently and this would permit a far flatter launch trajectory.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The vehicles would typically fly approximately tangentially to Earth's surface until leaving the atmosphere then perform a rocket burn to bridge the final delta-v to orbital velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] For spacecraft already in very low-orbit, air-breathing electric propulsion could use residual gases in the upper atmosphere as a propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Air-breathing electric propulsion could make a new class of long-lived, low-orbiting missions feasible on Earth, Mars or Venus.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] When a vehicle is to enter orbit around its destination planet, or when it is to land, it must adjust its velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] This can be done using any of the methods listed above (provided they can generate a high enough thrust), but there are methods that can take advantage of planetary atmospheres and/or surfaces.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Development of technologies will result in technical solutions that improve thrust levels, specific impulse, power, specific mass, (or specific power), volume, system mass, system complexity, operational complexity, commonality with other spacecraft systems, manufacturability, durability, and cost.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] These types of improvements will yield decreased transit times, increased payload mass, safer spacecraft, and decreased costs.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] In some instances, the development of technologies within this technology area will result in mission-enabling breakthroughs that will revolutionize space exploration.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] There is no single propulsion technology that will benefit all missions or mission types; the requirements for in-space propulsion vary widely according to their intended application.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] One institution focused on developing primary propulsion technologies aimed at benefitting near- and mid-term science missions by reducing cost, mass, and/or travel times is the Glenn Research Center (GRC).
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Electric propulsion architectures are of particular interest to the GRC, including ion and Hall thrusters.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] One system combines solar sails, a form of propellantless propulsion which relies on naturally occurring starlight for propulsion energy, and Hall thrusters.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Other propulsion technologies being developed include advanced chemical propulsion and aerocapture.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Sustainable Propulsion technologies, such as solar cells and electric propulsion systems powered by renewable energy, are gaining attention for their potential to provide solutions for space travel, whilst aiming for more efficient energy sources and lesser harmful emissions.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] However, those technologies may be limited in terms of thrust and scalability.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] In 2023, Boeing and Airbus are the leading research companies in Sustainable Propulsion for space applications in terms of patent family publications, but mostly focus on hydrogen/fuel cells and sustainable fuels.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The most important area in terms of patent family publications is electric propulsion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The number of patent family publications in electric propulsion systems has increased from only 70 in 2000 to 293 in 2023, with the top inventors being from China.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] The term "mission pull" defines a technology or a performance characteristic necessary to meet a planned NASA mission requirement.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Any other relationship between a technology and a mission (an alternate propulsion system, for example) is categorized as "technology push." Also, a space demonstration refers to the spaceflight of a scaled version of a particular technology or of a critical technology subsystem.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] On the other hand, a space validation would serve as a qualification flight for future mission implementation.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] A successful validation flight would not require any additional space testing of a particular technology before it can be adopted for a science or exploration mission.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Spacecraft propulsion systems are often first statically tested on Earth's surface, within the atmosphere but many systems require a vacuum chamber to test fully.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Rockets are usually tested at a rocket engine test facility well away from habitation and other buildings for safety reasons.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Ion drives are far less dangerous and require much less stringent safety, usually only a moderately large vacuum chamber is needed.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] Static firing of engines are done at ground test facilities, and systems which cannot be adequately tested on the ground and require launches may be employed at a launch site.
[src:rocket-propulsion/spacecraft-propulsion] In science fiction, space ships use various means to travel, some of them scientifically plausible (like solar sails or ramjets), others, mostly or entirely fictitious (like anti-gravity, warp drive, spindizzy or hyperspace travel).
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] It serves as a measure of how efficiently an engine, such as a rocket or jet engine, generates thrust from propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] *I*sp is the effective exhaust velocity used in the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation which calculates how much a vehicle's velocity can be changed with a given quantity of fuel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Reaction engines, such as rockets and jet engines propel a vehicle by expelling mass in one direction, which pushes the vehicle in the other direction according to Newton's third law of motion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] This expelled mass is called the *reaction mass*.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] An engine can push harder if it expels the reaction mass at a higher exhaust velocity $v_{e}$ , or expels mass at a faster rate, ${\frac {\mathrm {d} m}{\mathrm {d} t}}$ .
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] If this is integrated over time, the result is the total change in momentum.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Dividing by the mass shows that the specific impulse is equal to the exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] In practice, the specific impulse is usually lower than the actual physical exhaust velocity due to inefficiencies in the rocket, and thus corresponds to an "effective" exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The specific impulse $I_{\text{sp}}$ in units of velocity *is defined by* $T_{\text{avg}}=I_{\text{sp}}{\frac {\mathrm {d} m}{\mathrm {d} t}},$ where $T_{\text{avg}}$ is the average thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The practical meaning of the measurement varies with different types of engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Car engines consume onboard fuel, breathe environmental air to burn the fuel, and push against the ground beneath them.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] In this case, *I*sp is momentum per fuel burned.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Chemical rocket engines, by contrast, carry their fuel, oxidizer, and reaction mass with them, so *I*sp is momentum per reaction mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Airplane engines are in the middle, as they only push against airflow through the engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Some of this reaction mass is carried with them, and some is breathed from the air.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Therefore, "specific impulse" could be taken to mean either "per reaction mass", as with a rocket, or "per fuel burned" as with cars.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The latter is the traditional and more common choice.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Because of these differences, specific impulse is not directly comparable between different types of engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Specific impulse can be taken as a measure of efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] In cars and planes, it typically corresponds with fuel efficiency, i.e. the distance travelled per unit mass or volume of fuel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The difference between $m_{0}$ and $m_{\text{f}}$ is the reaction mass that was expelled.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] For any chemical rocket engine, the momentum transfer efficiency depends heavily on the effectiveness of the nozzle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The nozzle is the primary means of converting reactant energy (e.g. thermal or pressure energy) into a flow of momentum moving the same direction.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Nozzle shape and effectiveness has a great impact on total momentum transfer from the reaction mass to the rocket.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The efficiency of the conversion of input energy to reactant energy also affects *I*sp, either thermal energy in combustion engines or electrical energy in ion engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] This efficiency determines the amount of delta-v a rocket can perform with a given load of fuel.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Optimizing the tradeoffs between fuel quantity and specific impulse is one of the fundamental engineering challenges in rocketry.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Although the specific impulse has units of velocity, it almost never corresponds to an actual physical velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] In chemical and cold gas rockets, the shape of the nozzle has a high impact on the energy-to-momentum conversion.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] There are other sources of losses and inefficiencies as well, such as the details of the chemical combustion in such engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The physical exhaust velocity is higher than the "effective exhaust velocity", which is the "velocity" of the specific impulse.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The momentum exchanged and the mass used to generate it *are* physically real measurements.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Typically, rocket nozzles work better when the ambient pressure is lower, such as in space versus in the atmosphere.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Engines are typically described by a sea-level *I*sp, and a vacuum *I*sp, which is higher.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Ion engines, however, do not use a nozzle, although they have other sources of losses so that the momentum transferred is lower than the physical exhaust velocity of their reaction mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] It is common to express specific impulse as the product of two numbers: a characteristic velocity $c^{*}$ , which summarizes combustion-chamber performance into a quantity with units of speed, and a thrust coefficient $C_{F}$ , which is a dimensionless quantity that summarizes nozzle performance.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Physically, *I*sp measured in seconds is the amount of time a rocket engine can generate thrust, given a quantity of propellant whose weight (under *g*0) is equal to the engine's thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] It is the length of time that the engine can produce 1 kgf (or 1 lbf) of thrust from 1 kg (or 1 lb) of propellant.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Although the car industry almost never uses specific impulse on any practical level, the measure can be defined, and makes good contrast against other engine types.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Car engines breathe external air to combust their fuel, and (via the wheels) react against the ground.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The only meaningful way to interpret "specific impulse" is as "thrust per fuelflow", although one must also specify if the force is measured at the crankshaft or at the wheels, since there are transmission losses.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Such a measure corresponds to fuel mileage.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] In an aerodynamic context, there are similarities to both cars and rockets.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Like cars, airplane engines breathe outside air; unlike cars they react only against fluids flowing through the engine (including the propellers as applicable).
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] There are several possible ways to interpret "specific impulse": as thrust per fuel flow, as thrust per breathing-flow, or as thrust per "turbine-flow" (i.e. excluding air though the propeller/bypass fan).
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Since the air breathed is not a direct cost, with wide engineering leeway on how much to breathe, the industry traditionally chooses the "thrust per fuel flow" interpretation with its focus on cost efficiency.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] In this interpretation, the resulting specific impulse numbers are much higher than for rocket engines, although this comparison is quite different — one is with and the other is without reaction mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] It exemplifies the advantage an airplane engine has over a rocket due to not having to carry the air it uses.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] As with all kinds of engines, there are many engineering choices and tradeoffs that affect specific impulse.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Nonlinear air resistance and the engine's inability to keep a high specific impulse at a fast burn rate are limiting factors to the fuel consumption rate.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] As with rocket engines, the interpretation of specific impulse as a "velocity" does not actually correspond to the physical exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Since the usual interpretation excludes much of the reaction mass, the physical velocity of the reactants downstream is much lower than the effective exhaust velocity suggested from the Isp.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Specific impulse should not be confused with energy efficiency, which can decrease as specific impulse increases, since propulsion systems that give high specific impulse require high energy to do so.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Specific impulse should not be confused with total thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Thrust is the force supplied by the engine and depends on the propellant mass flow through the engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Specific impulse measures the thrust *per* propellant mass flow.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Thrust and specific impulse are related by the design and propellants of the engine in question, but this relationship is tenuous: in most cases, high thrust and high specific impulse are mutually exclusive engineering goals.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] For example, LH2/LO2 bipropellant produces higher *I*sp (due to higher chemical energy and lower exhaust molecular mass) but lower thrust than RP-1/LO2 (due to higher density and propellant flow).
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] In many cases, propulsion systems with very high specific impulse—some ion thrusters reach 25–35 times better *I*sp than chemical engines—produce correspondingly low thrust.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] When calculating specific impulse, only propellant carried with the vehicle before use is counted, in the standard interpretation.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] This usage best corresponds to the cost of operating the vehicle.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] For a chemical rocket, unlike a plane or car, the propellant mass therefore would include both fuel and oxidizer.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] For any vehicle, optimizing for specific impulse is generally not the same as optimizing for total performance or total cost.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] In rocketry, a heavier engine with a higher specific impulse may not be as effective in gaining altitude, distance, or velocity as a lighter engine with a lower specific impulse, especially if the latter engine possesses a higher thrust-to-weight ratio.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] This is a significant reason for most rocket designs having multiple stages.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The first stage can optimized for high thrust to effectively fight gravity drag and air drag, while the later stages operating strictly in orbit and in vacuum can be more easily optimized for higher specific impulse, especially for high delta-v orbits.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The amount of propellant could be defined either in units of mass or weight.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] If mass is used, specific impulse is an impulse per unit of mass, which dimensional analysis shows to be equivalent to units of speed; this interpretation is commonly labeled the *effective exhaust velocity*.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] If a force-based unit system is used, impulse is divided by propellant weight (weight is a measure of force), resulting in units of time.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The problem with weight, as a measure of quantity, is that it depends on the acceleration applied to the propellant, which is arbitrary with no relation to the design of the engine.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Historically, standard gravity was the reference conversion between weight and mass.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Measuring specific impulse by propellant mass gives it the same meaning for a car at sea level, an airplane at cruising altitude, or a helicopter on Mars.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] No matter the choice of mass or weight, the resulting quotient of "velocity" or "time" usually doesn't correspond directly to an actual velocity or time.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Due to various losses in real engines, the actual exhaust velocity is different from the *I*sp "velocity" (and for cars there isn't even a sensible definition of "actual exhaust velocity").
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Rather, the specific impulse is just that: a physical momentum from a physical quantity of propellant (be that in mass or weight).
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The most common unit for specific impulse is the second, as values are identical regardless of whether the calculations are done in SI, imperial, or US customary units.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Nearly all manufacturers quote their engine performance in seconds, and the unit is also useful for specifying aircraft engine performance.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The use of metres per second to specify effective exhaust velocity is also reasonably common.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] The unit is intuitive when describing rocket engines, although the effective exhaust speed of the engines may be significantly different from the actual exhaust speed, especially in gas-generator cycle engines.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] For airbreathing jet engines, the effective exhaust velocity does not account for the mass of the air used (as the air is taken in from the environment), although it can still be used for comparison purposes.
[src:rocket-propulsion/specific-impulse] Metres per second are numerically equivalent to newton-seconds per kg (N·s/kg), and SI measurements of specific impulse can be written in terms of either units interchangeably.
